00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:55.480 align:middle line:84%
Carl Sagan famously
said that understanding

00:01:55.480 --> 00:01:57.880 align:middle line:90%
is a kind of ecstasy.

00:01:57.880 --> 00:02:00.550 align:middle line:84%
And he also coined
the term wonder

00:02:00.550 --> 00:02:04.240 align:middle line:84%
junkie to describe that
insatiable curiosity that

00:02:04.240 --> 00:02:07.180 align:middle line:84%
haunts our dreams, the warm at
the core, the thing that makes

00:02:07.180 --> 00:02:09.699 align:middle line:84%
us look at the
cosmos, at the stars,

00:02:09.699 --> 00:02:12.310 align:middle line:84%
and at the perimeters of
our own minds to try to make

00:02:12.310 --> 00:02:13.760 align:middle line:90%
sense of what is going on.

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:15.070 align:middle line:90%
What is shaping our world?

00:02:15.070 --> 00:02:16.060 align:middle line:90%
Where are we going?

00:02:16.060 --> 00:02:17.240 align:middle line:90%
Where have we come from?

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:18.610 align:middle line:90%
What does it mean?

00:02:18.610 --> 00:02:22.300 align:middle line:84%
And also, how to make sure
that our understanding

00:02:22.300 --> 00:02:26.200 align:middle line:84%
of the great mysteries doesn't
get caught up in too much woo.

00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:30.850 align:middle line:84%
Because poetry is beautiful, but
science is just as beautiful.

00:02:30.850 --> 00:02:36.130 align:middle line:84%
And so today, we'll kind of
look at both sides of that coin.

00:02:36.130 --> 00:02:38.240 align:middle line:84%
So the title of this
conversation-- and it

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:39.490 align:middle line:90%
is going to be a conversation.

00:02:39.490 --> 00:02:44.245 align:middle line:84%
I'm just kind of framing
it, is we are the gods now.

00:02:44.245 --> 00:02:46.090 align:middle line:90%
Now, what does that mean?

00:02:46.090 --> 00:02:49.600 align:middle line:84%
Now, of course, that's a kind
of heretical thing, right?

00:02:49.600 --> 00:02:51.280 align:middle line:90%
To take claim over that.

00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:52.870 align:middle line:90%
We are the gods now.

00:02:52.870 --> 00:02:54.170 align:middle line:90%
I mean, how dare we, right?

00:02:54.170 --> 00:02:56.350 align:middle line:90%
Where is the cosmic humility?

00:02:56.350 --> 00:02:58.240 align:middle line:84%
We should bow down
before the cosmos

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:00.100 align:middle line:84%
and bow down before
the great mystery.

00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:02.470 align:middle line:84%
But it's not just
about that, right?

00:03:02.470 --> 00:03:05.350 align:middle line:84%
Carl Sagan said, we are a way
for the cosmos to know itself.

00:03:05.350 --> 00:03:06.470 align:middle line:90%
We are of nature.

00:03:06.470 --> 00:03:07.390 align:middle line:90%
We come from nature.

00:03:07.390 --> 00:03:09.070 align:middle line:90%
We are nature.

00:03:09.070 --> 00:03:11.580 align:middle line:84%
The difference is that we
can steward our own destiny.

00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:13.390 align:middle line:90%
We can govern our own path.

00:03:13.390 --> 00:03:16.630 align:middle line:84%
I am the captain of my faith,
or I'm the captain of my soul

00:03:16.630 --> 00:03:18.610 align:middle line:84%
or whatever the
hell that quote is.

00:03:18.610 --> 00:03:22.810 align:middle line:84%
But the point being that we have
this immense creative capacity

00:03:22.810 --> 00:03:25.540 align:middle line:84%
to engender our
dreams, to sort of

00:03:25.540 --> 00:03:29.560 align:middle line:84%
actualize our minds, to
manifest our imagination.

00:03:29.560 --> 00:03:31.840 align:middle line:84%
And we've created tools
that are giving us the power

00:03:31.840 --> 00:03:34.660 align:middle line:84%
to shape the world, to transform
the world, to impact the world,

00:03:34.660 --> 00:03:38.780 align:middle line:84%
to create and recreate the world
and also, to destroy the world.

00:03:38.780 --> 00:03:42.130 align:middle line:84%
And so as Stewart Brand
said, we are as gods

00:03:42.130 --> 00:03:43.630 align:middle line:84%
and might as well
get good at it.

00:03:43.630 --> 00:03:46.060 align:middle line:84%
So that's kind of the
framing, the context,

00:03:46.060 --> 00:03:48.010 align:middle line:84%
and the background
behind what we're

00:03:48.010 --> 00:03:50.980 align:middle line:90%
going to talk about today.

00:03:50.980 --> 00:03:54.850 align:middle line:84%
So we'd like to start first
with this notion of technology.

00:03:54.850 --> 00:03:57.890 align:middle line:84%
Steven Kotler co-wrote a book
with Peter Diamandis called

00:03:57.890 --> 00:03:58.690 align:middle line:90%
"Abundance--

00:03:58.690 --> 00:04:01.883 align:middle line:84%
Why the Future will be
Better Than You Think."

00:04:01.883 --> 00:04:03.550 align:middle line:84%
Most people are
terrified of the future.

00:04:03.550 --> 00:04:04.758 align:middle line:90%
They think of climate change.

00:04:04.758 --> 00:04:06.340 align:middle line:90%
They think of runaway AI.

00:04:06.340 --> 00:04:08.500 align:middle line:84%
They think of technology,
robot overlords taking

00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:10.000 align:middle line:84%
over the world, and
everything going

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.970 align:middle line:84%
to shit when, in fact,
there is remarkable progress

00:04:12.970 --> 00:04:14.890 align:middle line:84%
across many fields
in technology.

00:04:14.890 --> 00:04:16.420 align:middle line:84%
And technology is
advancing at rates

00:04:16.420 --> 00:04:18.410 align:middle line:90%
we can't even begin to fathom.

00:04:18.410 --> 00:04:20.760 align:middle line:84%
So let's just kind
of start with that.

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:22.227 align:middle line:90%
Steven--

00:04:22.227 --> 00:04:23.560 align:middle line:90%
>> Is there a question in there?

00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:24.360 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, sure.

00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:25.300 align:middle line:90%
Well, yeah.

00:04:25.300 --> 00:04:28.900 align:middle line:84%
The question is, what comes
to mind for you when you think

00:04:28.900 --> 00:04:30.910 align:middle line:84%
of the astounding
progress that we're seeing

00:04:30.910 --> 00:04:33.260 align:middle line:90%
in technology and innovation?

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:35.380 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you're best friends
with Peter Diamandis.

00:04:35.380 --> 00:04:36.760 align:middle line:84%
The guy is running around
the world talking about how

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:38.010 align:middle line:90%
we're going to save the world.

00:04:38.010 --> 00:04:40.933 align:middle line:84%
So how are we going to save
the world using technology?

00:04:40.933 --> 00:04:42.850 align:middle line:84%
>> You know how we're
going to save the world,

00:04:42.850 --> 00:04:43.810 align:middle line:84%
but we'll come back
to that answer.

00:04:43.810 --> 00:04:44.260 align:middle line:90%
>> Great.

00:04:44.260 --> 00:04:46.470 align:middle line:84%
>> I want to start with the
speed of technology, because--

00:04:46.470 --> 00:04:46.690 align:middle line:90%
>> Great.

00:04:46.690 --> 00:04:48.815 align:middle line:84%
>> --it's useful to put a
little context around it.

00:04:48.815 --> 00:04:51.440 align:middle line:84%
When Peter and I wrote
"Abundance" 10 years ago,

00:04:51.440 --> 00:04:54.910 align:middle line:84%
I guess, "Abundance" was about
individual lines of technology

00:04:54.910 --> 00:04:56.500 align:middle line:84%
that were accelerating
exponentially,

00:04:56.500 --> 00:04:58.360 align:middle line:84%
meaning they're doubling
at a periodic rate.

00:04:58.360 --> 00:04:59.985 align:middle line:84%
Computers are the
great example, right?

00:04:59.985 --> 00:05:02.020 align:middle line:84%
Every 18 months, they
get twice as fast,

00:05:02.020 --> 00:05:04.390 align:middle line:84%
but the cost stays the same
That's an exponential growth

00:05:04.390 --> 00:05:05.190 align:middle line:90%
curve.

00:05:05.190 --> 00:05:07.840 align:middle line:84%
And it starts out really
slow, and it gets really fast,

00:05:07.840 --> 00:05:08.960 align:middle line:90%
really quickly.

00:05:08.960 --> 00:05:12.190 align:middle line:84%
So if I take 30 exponential
steps or 30 regular steps

00:05:12.190 --> 00:05:13.070 align:middle line:90%
from right here--

00:05:13.070 --> 00:05:14.470 align:middle line:90%
1, 2, 3, 4, 5--

00:05:14.470 --> 00:05:16.030 align:middle line:90%
I end up 30 feet away.

00:05:16.030 --> 00:05:17.630 align:middle line:90%
Exponential steps-- it doubles.

00:05:17.630 --> 00:05:20.110 align:middle line:84%
So 1 becomes 2,
becomes 4, becomes 8.

00:05:20.110 --> 00:05:21.540 align:middle line:90%
I take 30 exponential steps.

00:05:21.540 --> 00:05:22.540 align:middle line:90%
I'm a billion feet away.

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:25.070 align:middle line:84%
I've just orbited
the Earth 26 times.

00:05:25.070 --> 00:05:26.710 align:middle line:84%
So when we wrote
"Abundance," we were

00:05:26.710 --> 00:05:28.720 align:middle line:84%
talking about individual
lines of technology

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:29.650 align:middle line:90%
becoming exponential.

00:05:29.650 --> 00:05:31.150 align:middle line:84%
And a technology
becomes exponential

00:05:31.150 --> 00:05:32.680 align:middle line:90%
once it becomes digital.

00:05:32.680 --> 00:05:34.240 align:middle line:84%
Once a technology
becomes digital,

00:05:34.240 --> 00:05:36.070 align:middle line:84%
it jumps on the
back of Moore's law

00:05:36.070 --> 00:05:38.140 align:middle line:84%
and starts
accelerating this way.

00:05:38.140 --> 00:05:39.880 align:middle line:84%
And in "Abundance,"
we talked about 12

00:05:39.880 --> 00:05:43.240 align:middle line:84%
different exponential
technologies that are emerging.

00:05:43.240 --> 00:05:46.150 align:middle line:84%
What we're seeing today
is these individual lines

00:05:46.150 --> 00:05:48.730 align:middle line:84%
are starting to converge, and
they're starting to overlap.

00:05:48.730 --> 00:05:50.813 align:middle line:84%
And that's starting to
produce incredible effects.

00:05:50.813 --> 00:05:54.160 align:middle line:84%
Ray Kurzweil, who's the
head of AI at Google

00:05:54.160 --> 00:05:56.170 align:middle line:84%
and who's been really
good with his predictions

00:05:56.170 --> 00:05:57.920 align:middle line:84%
about the future, has
estimated that we're

00:05:57.920 --> 00:06:01.060 align:middle line:84%
going to experience 20,000
years of technological change

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:02.170 align:middle line:90%
in the next hundred years.

00:06:02.170 --> 00:06:02.970 align:middle line:90%
Put it in context.

00:06:02.970 --> 00:06:05.100 align:middle line:84%
It means we're going to
go-- birth of agriculture

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:08.950 align:middle line:84%
to the Industrial Revolution
twice in 86 years.

00:06:08.950 --> 00:06:11.590 align:middle line:84%
That's the speed we're looking
at that, the speed of change

00:06:11.590 --> 00:06:15.500 align:middle line:84%
that's coming, which is
both amazing and terrifying

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:16.300 align:middle line:90%
at the same time.

00:06:16.300 --> 00:06:18.092 align:middle line:84%
And the answer, I think,
to your question--

00:06:18.092 --> 00:06:20.470 align:middle line:84%
this is what we
said in "Abundance."

00:06:20.470 --> 00:06:22.180 align:middle line:84%
And I think this is
exactly what Stewart

00:06:22.180 --> 00:06:25.480 align:middle line:84%
meant by we are as gods, we
might as well get good at it,

00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:30.210 align:middle line:84%
is we said at this point what
the world faces-- incredibly

00:06:30.210 --> 00:06:31.110 align:middle line:90%
difficult challenges.

00:06:31.110 --> 00:06:34.020 align:middle line:84%
Our technology gives us
the power to solve them,

00:06:34.020 --> 00:06:35.838 align:middle line:84%
but it won't do
it automatically.

00:06:35.838 --> 00:06:37.380 align:middle line:84%
This is not techno
utopianism, right?

00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:40.110 align:middle line:84%
It's going to require the
greatest cooperative effort

00:06:40.110 --> 00:06:42.210 align:middle line:90%
in history to pull this off.

00:06:42.210 --> 00:06:45.270 align:middle line:84%
So all it does is give us--
it gives us an escape valve.

00:06:45.270 --> 00:06:47.040 align:middle line:84%
We can do it, but
we better figure out

00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:47.430 align:middle line:90%
how to work together.

00:06:47.430 --> 00:06:48.230 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:06:48.230 --> 00:06:50.430 align:middle line:84%
Immense power, but also
immense responsibility.

00:06:50.430 --> 00:06:54.840 align:middle line:84%
And he got into this notion
of the exponential speed

00:06:54.840 --> 00:06:55.950 align:middle line:90%
of technological progress.

00:06:55.950 --> 00:06:58.710 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that 30-steps
example for me

00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:02.790 align:middle line:84%
became my sort of runaway train
to imagine the impossible,

00:07:02.790 --> 00:07:05.238 align:middle line:90%
because we have brains.

00:07:05.238 --> 00:07:06.780 align:middle line:84%
And Peter Diamandis
talks about this.

00:07:06.780 --> 00:07:08.288 align:middle line:84%
And Ray Kurzweil
talks about this.

00:07:08.288 --> 00:07:10.080 align:middle line:84%
We have brains that
evolved in a world that

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:11.580 align:middle line:90%
was linear and local.

00:07:11.580 --> 00:07:13.470 align:middle line:90%
We are wired.

00:07:13.470 --> 00:07:16.560 align:middle line:84%
Our intuition about change
over time is linear.

00:07:16.560 --> 00:07:18.567 align:middle line:84%
That's just what governs
our natural intuition.

00:07:18.567 --> 00:07:19.650 align:middle line:90%
>> It's weirder than that.

00:07:19.650 --> 00:07:22.380 align:middle line:84%
Kelly MacDonald did some
really cool research.

00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:24.960 align:middle line:84%
Most of us have a built-in
10-year time horizon.

00:07:24.960 --> 00:07:27.570 align:middle line:90%
We cannot see past 10 years.

00:07:27.570 --> 00:07:29.742 align:middle line:84%
So I run a company called
the EQ with some friends.

00:07:29.742 --> 00:07:31.200 align:middle line:84%
And we bring together
technologists

00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:33.870 align:middle line:84%
and environmentalists to solve
environmental challenges.

00:07:33.870 --> 00:07:36.300 align:middle line:84%
And we have a whole
retro-casting process that

00:07:36.300 --> 00:07:39.150 align:middle line:84%
we've developed to get people to
be able to see past 10 years--

00:07:39.150 --> 00:07:41.610 align:middle line:84%
>> If we could have
those exponential lenses,

00:07:41.610 --> 00:07:45.000 align:middle line:84%
we would gain so
much perspective.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:49.200 align:middle line:84%
So this notion of the 30 linear
steps getting you to 30 and 30

00:07:49.200 --> 00:07:51.330 align:middle line:84%
exponential steps getting
you to a billion--

00:07:51.330 --> 00:07:53.520 align:middle line:84%
just take-- pause on
that for a second, right?

00:07:53.520 --> 00:07:56.190 align:middle line:84%
Because we're calling this,
we are the gods now, right?

00:07:56.190 --> 00:08:02.250 align:middle line:84%
30 exponential steps gets you
a billion times farther, right?

00:08:02.250 --> 00:08:04.980 align:middle line:84%
And that exponential
progress is the reason

00:08:04.980 --> 00:08:08.250 align:middle line:84%
why the smart phone in
your pocket today that you

00:08:08.250 --> 00:08:09.930 align:middle line:84%
use every day that
you take for granted,

00:08:09.930 --> 00:08:12.090 align:middle line:84%
that you complain
when the signal drops,

00:08:12.090 --> 00:08:15.180 align:middle line:84%
is a million times cheaper,
a million times smaller,

00:08:15.180 --> 00:08:17.340 align:middle line:84%
and a thousand
times more powerful

00:08:17.340 --> 00:08:18.840 align:middle line:84%
than what used to
be a $60 million

00:08:18.840 --> 00:08:22.370 align:middle line:84%
supercomputer that was half a
building in size 40 years ago.

00:08:22.370 --> 00:08:26.610 align:middle line:84%
So it doesn't take you being an
engineer, or a mathematician,

00:08:26.610 --> 00:08:32.250 align:middle line:84%
or a technologist to just
grasp that kind of progress.

00:08:32.250 --> 00:08:35.400 align:middle line:84%
The supercomputer was the size
of this room 40 years ago.

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:36.870 align:middle line:90%
It cost $60 million.

00:08:36.870 --> 00:08:39.840 align:middle line:84%
And now, you can go to
an iPhone store, right?

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:41.760 align:middle line:84%
Go to an Apple
Store and buy this.

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:43.950 align:middle line:84%
And it's a million
times cheaper.

00:08:43.950 --> 00:08:45.540 align:middle line:90%
Million times cheaper.

00:08:45.540 --> 00:08:48.727 align:middle line:84%
For those who say these
tools are only for the rich,

00:08:48.727 --> 00:08:50.310 align:middle line:84%
it's a million times
cheaper than what

00:08:50.310 --> 00:08:53.940 align:middle line:84%
it used to be 40 years ago,
a million times smaller,

00:08:53.940 --> 00:08:57.100 align:middle line:84%
and a thousand
times more powerful.

00:08:57.100 --> 00:08:59.580 align:middle line:84%
So that means that, again,
as Kurzweil likes to say,

00:08:59.580 --> 00:09:02.970 align:middle line:84%
a young kid in Africa or
Mexico with a smart phone

00:09:02.970 --> 00:09:06.270 align:middle line:84%
has better communications
technology than a head of state

00:09:06.270 --> 00:09:08.303 align:middle line:90%
had 25 years ago.

00:09:08.303 --> 00:09:09.720 align:middle line:84%
So I don't give a
shit how cynical

00:09:09.720 --> 00:09:11.160 align:middle line:90%
you are, how skeptical you are.

00:09:11.160 --> 00:09:12.840 align:middle line:90%
That's a fact, right?

00:09:12.840 --> 00:09:16.200 align:middle line:84%
That's a fact that a young kid
with an internet connection

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:18.210 align:middle line:84%
on their phone has
better communications

00:09:18.210 --> 00:09:21.450 align:middle line:84%
technology than a
president had 25 years ago.

00:09:21.450 --> 00:09:22.920 align:middle line:90%
Undeniable progress.

00:09:22.920 --> 00:09:27.810 align:middle line:84%
Astounding supercomputers
in our pockets.

00:09:27.810 --> 00:09:30.900 align:middle line:84%
Now, this reminds me of
Steven Johnson's line

00:09:30.900 --> 00:09:33.142 align:middle line:84%
of the adjacent
possible from his book,

00:09:33.142 --> 00:09:34.350 align:middle line:90%
"Where Good Ideas Come From."

00:09:34.350 --> 00:09:36.240 align:middle line:84%
And he says the
adjacent possible

00:09:36.240 --> 00:09:38.220 align:middle line:84%
is a shadow from the
future that hovers

00:09:38.220 --> 00:09:40.620 align:middle line:84%
over the present, a
map of all the ways

00:09:40.620 --> 00:09:43.210 align:middle line:84%
in which the present
can reinvent itself.

00:09:43.210 --> 00:09:45.720 align:middle line:84%
So in terms of we
being the gods now,

00:09:45.720 --> 00:09:47.670 align:middle line:84%
we also have to start
thinking in terms

00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:49.830 align:middle line:84%
of adjacent
possibilities on the back

00:09:49.830 --> 00:09:52.270 align:middle line:90%
of exponential technologies.

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:55.340 align:middle line:84%
What are some of the scenarios,
and tools, and technologies

00:09:55.340 --> 00:09:57.390 align:middle line:84%
that you guys modeled
in "Abundance,"

00:09:57.390 --> 00:09:59.820 align:middle line:84%
like some shit that just like
blows your mind in terms of

00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:01.190 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:10:01.190 --> 00:10:04.440 align:middle line:84%
>> So Peter and I are working on
a new book that'll be out next

00:10:04.440 --> 00:10:07.215 align:middle line:84%
February, and it opens with
a chapter on the future

00:10:07.215 --> 00:10:08.190 align:middle line:90%
of transportation.

00:10:08.190 --> 00:10:12.240 align:middle line:84%
And it opens at
the Uber flying car

00:10:12.240 --> 00:10:15.730 align:middle line:84%
conference, which took place
in LA eight months ago.

00:10:15.730 --> 00:10:17.760 align:middle line:84%
And what you probably
don't know is

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:20.670 align:middle line:84%
that while Uber is going
to go autonomous completely

00:10:20.670 --> 00:10:25.010 align:middle line:84%
by 2019 and 2020, by
2023 in LA and Dallas,

00:10:25.010 --> 00:10:29.260 align:middle line:84%
we're going to have
flying autonomous taxis.

00:10:29.260 --> 00:10:31.920 align:middle line:84%
By the way, so I wrote a
story about a guy named

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:35.190 align:middle line:84%
Dezso Molnar, who's a friend
of mine, who invented probably

00:10:35.190 --> 00:10:37.500 align:middle line:84%
the world's first flying
car, flying helicopter that

00:10:37.500 --> 00:10:39.130 align:middle line:90%
actually flew and was usable.

00:10:39.130 --> 00:10:42.550 align:middle line:90%
This was 15 years ago.

00:10:42.550 --> 00:10:44.890 align:middle line:84%
And we've gone from
the very first one that

00:10:44.890 --> 00:10:47.050 align:middle line:84%
was a kit car in
somebody's garage

00:10:47.050 --> 00:10:51.140 align:middle line:84%
to taxis in three
years, four years--

00:10:51.140 --> 00:10:51.940 align:middle line:90%
flying cars.

00:10:51.940 --> 00:10:52.815 align:middle line:90%
So that's incredible.

00:10:52.815 --> 00:10:54.398 align:middle line:84%
The other one that
I always think of--

00:10:54.398 --> 00:10:56.493 align:middle line:84%
and this is an example
that I always sort of like

00:10:56.493 --> 00:10:58.660 align:middle line:84%
to give people when I think
about this, because it's

00:10:58.660 --> 00:11:00.310 align:middle line:90%
really personal.

00:11:00.310 --> 00:11:03.820 align:middle line:84%
Biotechnology is advancing
about four to five times

00:11:03.820 --> 00:11:05.010 align:middle line:90%
as fast as Moore's law.

00:11:05.010 --> 00:11:06.760 align:middle line:84%
So it is doubling
in power, roughly

00:11:06.760 --> 00:11:08.230 align:middle line:90%
every four to five months.

00:11:08.230 --> 00:11:11.600 align:middle line:84%
And what that means is every
day we manage to stay alive,

00:11:11.600 --> 00:11:14.290 align:middle line:84%
we gain five hours
of life expectancy.

00:11:14.290 --> 00:11:15.490 align:middle line:90%
No exercise required.

00:11:15.490 --> 00:11:16.804 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:16.804 --> 00:11:17.680 align:middle line:90%


00:11:17.680 --> 00:11:18.740 align:middle line:90%
That's incredible to me.

00:11:18.740 --> 00:11:19.540 align:middle line:90%
>> Wow.

00:11:19.540 --> 00:11:21.790 align:middle line:84%
>> That's the one that
always sort of blows my mind.

00:11:21.790 --> 00:11:23.500 align:middle line:84%
The other one that
blows my mind--

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:26.860 align:middle line:84%
so a bunch of years ago, I got a
chance to spend a bunch of time

00:11:26.860 --> 00:11:29.770 align:middle line:84%
with Hugh Herr, who's the head
of biomechatronics at MIT.

00:11:29.770 --> 00:11:32.660 align:middle line:90%
He is the first--

00:11:32.660 --> 00:11:34.690 align:middle line:84%
he created the world's
first bionic ankle,

00:11:34.690 --> 00:11:38.080 align:middle line:84%
which was the first
FDA-approved bionic body part.

00:11:38.080 --> 00:11:40.990 align:middle line:84%
And at the time,
six, seven years ago,

00:11:40.990 --> 00:11:43.090 align:middle line:84%
it was so robust
that soldiers were

00:11:43.090 --> 00:11:45.648 align:middle line:84%
returning to combat, wearing
them in Afghanistan and Iraq.

00:11:45.648 --> 00:11:46.940 align:middle line:90%
People were running triathlons.

00:11:46.940 --> 00:11:49.082 align:middle line:90%
So it's a real bionic body part.

00:11:49.082 --> 00:11:51.040 align:middle line:84%
And yet, because of the
speed of biotechnology,

00:11:51.040 --> 00:11:52.900 align:middle line:90%
it is so five years ago.

00:11:52.900 --> 00:11:55.380 align:middle line:84%
Today, 50% of the human body
is replaceable by bionics.

00:11:55.380 --> 00:11:56.180 align:middle line:90%
>> 50%?

00:11:56.180 --> 00:11:57.260 align:middle line:90%
>> 50%.

00:11:57.260 --> 00:12:00.630 align:middle line:84%
50% of you is going to get
swapped out, all right?

00:12:00.630 --> 00:12:03.810 align:middle line:84%
With 3D printing body
replacement body parts, right?

00:12:03.810 --> 00:12:04.610 align:middle line:90%
That's what's--

00:12:04.610 --> 00:12:05.470 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, yeah.

00:12:05.470 --> 00:12:07.960 align:middle line:90%
It resonates so deeply with me.

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:11.190 align:middle line:84%
Because I was deeply
affected by a book

00:12:11.190 --> 00:12:14.530 align:middle line:84%
I read by Ernest Becker,
called "The Denial of Death."

00:12:14.530 --> 00:12:16.270 align:middle line:84%
And the key idea
behind the book is

00:12:16.270 --> 00:12:19.170 align:middle line:84%
that the source of our
existential malaise,

00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:21.460 align:middle line:90%
our cosmological depression--

00:12:21.460 --> 00:12:24.190 align:middle line:84%
we are feeling so
small, is that we are

00:12:24.190 --> 00:12:25.780 align:middle line:90%
stuck in these mortal bodies.

00:12:25.780 --> 00:12:28.930 align:middle line:84%
But we can kind of contemplate
the infinite, right?

00:12:28.930 --> 00:12:31.800 align:middle line:84%
This idea that we've
emerged from nothing.

00:12:31.800 --> 00:12:32.715 align:middle line:90%
We have a name.

00:12:32.715 --> 00:12:37.030 align:middle line:84%
We have this consciousness of
self, this deep inner feeling,

00:12:37.030 --> 00:12:39.760 align:middle line:84%
this excruciating
inner yearning for life

00:12:39.760 --> 00:12:40.900 align:middle line:90%
and for self-expression.

00:12:40.900 --> 00:12:43.960 align:middle line:84%
We want to sing the songs
that orchestrate the universe.

00:12:43.960 --> 00:12:46.510 align:middle line:84%
We want to explore
wonders beyond measure.

00:12:46.510 --> 00:12:49.050 align:middle line:84%
We want to experience
transitory, enchanted moments

00:12:49.050 --> 00:12:50.800 align:middle line:84%
in which we can hold
our breath, compelled

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:53.650 align:middle line:84%
into aesthetic contemplations
we neither understand or desire,

00:12:53.650 --> 00:12:55.400 align:middle line:84%
face to face with
things that are measured

00:12:55.400 --> 00:12:57.220 align:middle line:90%
to our capacity for wonder.

00:12:57.220 --> 00:13:00.310 align:middle line:90%
I want to drink infinity, right?

00:13:00.310 --> 00:13:01.217 align:middle line:90%
And yet--

00:13:01.217 --> 00:13:02.800 align:middle line:84%
>> [INAUDIBLE],,
ladies and gentlemen.

00:13:02.800 --> 00:13:03.610 align:middle line:90%
>> --I'm bounded.

00:13:03.610 --> 00:13:04.410 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

00:13:04.410 --> 00:13:06.850 align:middle line:90%
I'm finite, right?

00:13:06.850 --> 00:13:09.190 align:middle line:84%
And that haunts my
dreams to no end.

00:13:09.190 --> 00:13:11.360 align:middle line:84%
I tell people jokingly,
but it's really true.

00:13:11.360 --> 00:13:12.610 align:middle line:90%
I'm like a damn hypochondriac.

00:13:12.610 --> 00:13:14.410 align:middle line:90%
How could you not be, right?

00:13:14.410 --> 00:13:16.600 align:middle line:90%
You're dependent on a heartbeat.

00:13:16.600 --> 00:13:19.150 align:middle line:84%
You have so much you want
to do, so much you want, so

00:13:19.150 --> 00:13:21.700 align:middle line:84%
many ways you want to express
yourselves, so many books

00:13:21.700 --> 00:13:24.700 align:middle line:84%
you want to read, so many
questions you want answered.

00:13:24.700 --> 00:13:27.700 align:middle line:84%
And then you get the flu, and
it knocks you on the damn floor.

00:13:27.700 --> 00:13:30.040 align:middle line:84%
An invisible force
takes away your agency,

00:13:30.040 --> 00:13:31.840 align:middle line:90%
shrinks you down to nothing.

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:34.450 align:middle line:84%
I mean, even the common
cold is existentially

00:13:34.450 --> 00:13:36.580 align:middle line:84%
disempowering for a
species that can put

00:13:36.580 --> 00:13:38.870 align:middle line:90%
a human being on the damn moon.

00:13:38.870 --> 00:13:43.150 align:middle line:84%
So when I think
of biotechnology,

00:13:43.150 --> 00:13:46.630 align:middle line:84%
biotechnology means mastering
the information processes

00:13:46.630 --> 00:13:47.680 align:middle line:90%
of biology, right?

00:13:47.680 --> 00:13:49.780 align:middle line:84%
Because it really starts
to get interesting

00:13:49.780 --> 00:13:51.970 align:middle line:84%
when you realize that
we are made of language,

00:13:51.970 --> 00:13:55.090 align:middle line:84%
that we are alphabetic all the
way down, that we are literally

00:13:55.090 --> 00:13:56.680 align:middle line:90%
made of code, right?

00:13:56.680 --> 00:13:59.680 align:middle line:84%
Biology is software that
writes its own hardware.

00:13:59.680 --> 00:14:02.210 align:middle line:84%
Our genes are little
software programs.

00:14:02.210 --> 00:14:03.760 align:middle line:84%
So we are literally
made of language.

00:14:03.760 --> 00:14:06.250 align:middle line:84%
We are literally
information, right?

00:14:06.250 --> 00:14:08.680 align:middle line:84%
And so if we could learn
to master that language,

00:14:08.680 --> 00:14:11.920 align:middle line:84%
manipulate that language,
reprogram our genes away

00:14:11.920 --> 00:14:13.930 align:middle line:84%
from disease, away
from aging, so

00:14:13.930 --> 00:14:16.810 align:middle line:84%
that people don't die
from cancer, but also

00:14:16.810 --> 00:14:18.610 align:middle line:90%
don't die from time.

00:14:18.610 --> 00:14:20.710 align:middle line:90%
Why should time kill us?

00:14:20.710 --> 00:14:24.340 align:middle line:84%
If you're a bad person, if you
hurt other people, then, OK.

00:14:24.340 --> 00:14:25.510 align:middle line:90%
Put you in a cell.

00:14:25.510 --> 00:14:31.240 align:middle line:84%
But if you're like a curious
student of the cosmos,

00:14:31.240 --> 00:14:32.740 align:middle line:90%
I want infinity.

00:14:32.740 --> 00:14:34.550 align:middle line:90%
Nothing less will do.

00:14:34.550 --> 00:14:35.350 align:middle line:90%
Eternity.

00:14:35.350 --> 00:14:37.150 align:middle line:84%
Nothing is real
that is not eternal,

00:14:37.150 --> 00:14:40.910 align:middle line:84%
said Miguel [INAUDIBLE],,
in tragic sense of life.

00:14:40.910 --> 00:14:43.030 align:middle line:84%
And so when I hear that
gene sequencing is going

00:14:43.030 --> 00:14:47.050 align:middle line:84%
three times faster than
Moore's law, three times faster

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:50.230 align:middle line:84%
than exponential, and I hear
Craig Venter who synthesized

00:14:50.230 --> 00:14:52.768 align:middle line:84%
the first synthetic
organisms say, when asked,

00:14:52.768 --> 00:14:54.310 align:middle line:84%
do you worry that
you're playing God?

00:14:54.310 --> 00:14:56.230 align:middle line:90%
He said who's playing?

00:14:56.230 --> 00:14:58.030 align:middle line:90%
Who's playing?

00:14:58.030 --> 00:15:01.510 align:middle line:84%
When I see Larry Page create
Calico, the California life

00:15:01.510 --> 00:15:03.880 align:middle line:84%
extension company-- he's
the co-founder of Google,

00:15:03.880 --> 00:15:05.622 align:middle line:84%
creating a software
company for biology,

00:15:05.622 --> 00:15:07.330 align:middle line:84%
getting a cover on
"Time" magazine called

00:15:07.330 --> 00:15:09.760 align:middle line:90%
"Google and the End of Death."

00:15:09.760 --> 00:15:12.970 align:middle line:84%
This is where we're heading,
and we shouldn't cower.

00:15:12.970 --> 00:15:16.060 align:middle line:84%
And we shouldn't shrink down
before this ambition, right?

00:15:16.060 --> 00:15:18.490 align:middle line:84%
But we should rise up
before this ambition.

00:15:18.490 --> 00:15:20.740 align:middle line:84%
As Alan Harrington wrote
in "The Immortalist,"

00:15:20.740 --> 00:15:25.420 align:middle line:84%
having invented the gods,
we can now turn into them.

00:15:25.420 --> 00:15:28.210 align:middle line:84%
And I think nothing
else will do.

00:15:28.210 --> 00:15:32.050 align:middle line:84%
And so when are we going to
see radical life extension,

00:15:32.050 --> 00:15:35.620 align:middle line:84%
like true radical
life extension?

00:15:35.620 --> 00:15:41.780 align:middle line:84%
>> So one, you like
people more than I do.

00:15:41.780 --> 00:15:42.690 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:42.690 --> 00:15:43.490 align:middle line:90%


00:15:43.490 --> 00:15:46.280 align:middle line:84%
So you might be more hopeful
about this particular thing

00:15:46.280 --> 00:15:47.300 align:middle line:90%
than I am.

00:15:47.300 --> 00:15:53.330 align:middle line:90%
But ignoring that, no, we just--

00:15:53.330 --> 00:15:59.500 align:middle line:84%
I just actually wrote
the longevity chapter

00:15:59.500 --> 00:16:02.060 align:middle line:90%
for "Convergence" with Peter.

00:16:02.060 --> 00:16:04.430 align:middle line:84%
And it is, by the way, hard
to find a longevity company

00:16:04.430 --> 00:16:06.980 align:middle line:84%
in the world right now that
my co-author is not somehow

00:16:06.980 --> 00:16:09.860 align:middle line:90%
involved in, which is odd.

00:16:09.860 --> 00:16:11.630 align:middle line:84%
I think it's
getting interesting.

00:16:11.630 --> 00:16:15.320 align:middle line:84%
I think we're going to
start seeing stem cells.

00:16:15.320 --> 00:16:18.440 align:middle line:84%
Next 10 years-- we'll
start seeing stem cells.

00:16:18.440 --> 00:16:22.220 align:middle line:84%
Replacement body parts are
coming a lot faster than you

00:16:22.220 --> 00:16:23.270 align:middle line:90%
could possibly imagine.

00:16:23.270 --> 00:16:26.430 align:middle line:84%
Again, 10-year,
12-year time horizon.

00:16:26.430 --> 00:16:30.650 align:middle line:84%
And there's some just amazing
medical technology that's

00:16:30.650 --> 00:16:33.080 align:middle line:90%
also moving this quickly.

00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:35.210 align:middle line:84%
So it's going to--
the next 10, 12 years

00:16:35.210 --> 00:16:37.400 align:middle line:84%
is when I think we're
going to start seeing

00:16:37.400 --> 00:16:39.500 align:middle line:90%
the first edge of those things.

00:16:39.500 --> 00:16:40.300 align:middle line:90%
>> 10 to 12?

00:16:40.300 --> 00:16:41.672 align:middle line:90%
>> 10 to 12 years.

00:16:41.672 --> 00:16:43.130 align:middle line:84%
>> Actual, measurable
[INAUDIBLE]..

00:16:43.130 --> 00:16:45.350 align:middle line:84%
>> I want to go back
to, why are you so--

00:16:45.350 --> 00:16:49.028 align:middle line:84%
aren't you curious
about what's next?

00:16:49.028 --> 00:16:51.695 align:middle line:84%
>> I think I'm just afraid
of being disappointed.

00:16:51.695 --> 00:16:53.030 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:53.030 --> 00:16:54.310 align:middle line:90%
>> OK, fair point.

00:16:54.310 --> 00:16:57.640 align:middle line:84%
>> Plus, I also think we
have such an immense creative

00:16:57.640 --> 00:17:02.080 align:middle line:84%
capacity right now to kind
of warp the world and make it

00:17:02.080 --> 00:17:03.283 align:middle line:90%
better.

00:17:03.283 --> 00:17:04.450 align:middle line:90%
We could also make it worse.

00:17:04.450 --> 00:17:05.930 align:middle line:84%
We've made it
worse in some ways.

00:17:05.930 --> 00:17:08.220 align:middle line:84%
But in so many ways, we've
made it better, right?

00:17:08.220 --> 00:17:11.199 align:middle line:84%
Terence McKenna's wonderful
line that the human-made world

00:17:11.199 --> 00:17:13.870 align:middle line:84%
is the condensation
of human imagination.

00:17:13.870 --> 00:17:15.870 align:middle line:84%
Or David Deutsch in "The
Beginning of Infinity,"

00:17:15.870 --> 00:17:17.912 align:middle line:84%
where he talks about the
notion of the topography

00:17:17.912 --> 00:17:21.540 align:middle line:84%
of any great city like
Manhattan or Los Angeles,

00:17:21.540 --> 00:17:23.290 align:middle line:84%
and that the physical
topography of a city

00:17:23.290 --> 00:17:25.900 align:middle line:84%
is shaped more by
the forces of mind

00:17:25.900 --> 00:17:29.470 align:middle line:84%
by creativity, by economics,
by trade, by imagination

00:17:29.470 --> 00:17:31.540 align:middle line:90%
than by the forces of geology.

00:17:31.540 --> 00:17:34.310 align:middle line:90%
So mind has trumped geology.

00:17:34.310 --> 00:17:36.130 align:middle line:84%
And so it's like when
we think of ourselves

00:17:36.130 --> 00:17:38.215 align:middle line:84%
and what we are, like
holy shit, right?

00:17:38.215 --> 00:17:40.090 align:middle line:84%
We are this emergent
property of the universe

00:17:40.090 --> 00:17:41.980 align:middle line:90%
that can self-modify.

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:45.100 align:middle line:84%
And that is like a coral
reef-like animal, an extruder

00:17:45.100 --> 00:17:46.390 align:middle line:90%
of technological material.

00:17:46.390 --> 00:17:48.030 align:middle line:84%
We take in matter
of low organization.

