makes us feel.

00:26:56.110 --> 00:26:57.700 align:middle line:84%
And what's
interesting about that

00:26:57.700 --> 00:27:00.100 align:middle line:84%
is for every decision, every
action to flow seamlessly,

00:27:00.100 --> 00:27:02.050 align:middle line:84%
perfectly, effortlessly
from the last,

00:27:02.050 --> 00:27:03.790 align:middle line:84%
you have kind of a
shorthand definition

00:27:03.790 --> 00:27:06.430 align:middle line:84%
of what flow kind of is
under the hood, which

00:27:06.430 --> 00:27:09.820 align:middle line:84%
is as close to high-speed,
near perfect decision-making

00:27:09.820 --> 00:27:10.990 align:middle line:90%
as we can get.

00:27:10.990 --> 00:27:12.080 align:middle line:90%
Interesting.

00:27:12.080 --> 00:27:14.980 align:middle line:84%
I said as close to, not
perfect decision-making.

00:27:14.980 --> 00:27:17.170 align:middle line:84%
Scot Schmidt, one of the
early extreme skiers,

00:27:17.170 --> 00:27:19.450 align:middle line:84%
used to say flow makes
me feel like Superman,

00:27:19.450 --> 00:27:22.060 align:middle line:84%
up until the moment
I'm not, right?

00:27:22.060 --> 00:27:24.530 align:middle line:90%
Word of caution on that one.

00:27:24.530 --> 00:27:25.630 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh, well.

00:27:25.630 --> 00:27:28.460 align:middle line:84%
>> What's interesting about
flow is the numbers are all over

00:27:28.460 --> 00:27:29.260 align:middle line:90%
the place.

00:27:29.260 --> 00:27:31.720 align:middle line:84%
But some studies have
found productivity goes up

00:27:31.720 --> 00:27:33.760 align:middle line:90%
500%, creativity--

00:27:33.760 --> 00:27:35.860 align:middle line:90%
200 to 400%.

00:27:35.860 --> 00:27:38.680 align:middle line:84%
And we understand kind
of the neurobiology

00:27:38.680 --> 00:27:40.395 align:middle line:90%
underneath all of this.

00:27:40.395 --> 00:27:41.770 align:middle line:84%
What's really
getting interesting

00:27:41.770 --> 00:27:44.470 align:middle line:90%
is neuroscience, biotechnology.

00:27:44.470 --> 00:27:47.590 align:middle line:84%
These are accelerating fields,
again, exponentially moving

00:27:47.590 --> 00:27:48.460 align:middle line:90%
forward.

00:27:48.460 --> 00:27:53.350 align:middle line:84%
So when I started
this work in 1999,

00:27:53.350 --> 00:27:55.090 align:middle line:84%
when I first started
doing flow research,

00:27:55.090 --> 00:27:57.145 align:middle line:84%
I remember being on the phone
with Dr. Andrew Newberg.

00:27:57.145 --> 00:27:58.570 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if you guys
are familiar with him.

00:27:58.570 --> 00:28:00.550 align:middle line:84%
He was the University
of Pennsylvania

00:28:00.550 --> 00:28:04.690 align:middle line:84%
neuroscientist who did the
first work on cosmic unity.

00:28:04.690 --> 00:28:06.580 align:middle line:84%
He took Tibetan,
Buddhist, and Franciscan

00:28:06.580 --> 00:28:08.290 align:middle line:84%
nuns experiencing
oneness with everything

00:28:08.290 --> 00:28:11.375 align:middle line:84%
and put them into an fMRI
and tried to figure out

00:28:11.375 --> 00:28:12.250 align:middle line:90%
where that came from.

00:28:12.250 --> 00:28:13.900 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, if you're
going to my talk tomorrow,

00:28:13.900 --> 00:28:16.220 align:middle line:84%
I will tell that story and talk
about where that came from.

00:28:16.220 --> 00:28:17.420 align:middle line:90%
We're going to ignore that.

00:28:17.420 --> 00:28:18.950 align:middle line:84%
>> Go to his talk
tomorrow, guys.

00:28:18.950 --> 00:28:20.800 align:middle line:90%
It's going to be awesome.

00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:26.693 align:middle line:84%
>> But I remember talking to
him about flow at the time.

00:28:26.693 --> 00:28:28.360 align:middle line:84%
And I said, do you
think in our lifetime

00:28:28.360 --> 00:28:29.757 align:middle line:90%
we're ever going to decode this?

00:28:29.757 --> 00:28:31.090 align:middle line:90%
Are we going to figure this out?

00:28:31.090 --> 00:28:34.100 align:middle line:84%
And both of us were sure
it would not happen.

00:28:34.100 --> 00:28:36.970 align:middle line:84%
And here we are--
couple decades later.

00:28:36.970 --> 00:28:39.610 align:middle line:84%
And the state of ultimate
human performance-- we

00:28:39.610 --> 00:28:41.140 align:middle line:84%
are now starting
to pick it apart.

00:28:41.140 --> 00:28:43.145 align:middle line:84%
We understand what
it does to the brain.

00:28:43.145 --> 00:28:45.020 align:middle line:84%
We understand what it
does to the physiology.

00:28:45.020 --> 00:28:45.760 align:middle line:90%
It's not all the way there.

00:28:45.760 --> 00:28:47.380 align:middle line:84%
And there's huge
gaps in the research

00:28:47.380 --> 00:28:49.130 align:middle line:90%
we can drive buses through.

00:28:49.130 --> 00:28:50.770 align:middle line:84%
But this is ultimate
even performance

00:28:50.770 --> 00:28:52.690 align:middle line:90%
that we're being able to decode.

00:28:52.690 --> 00:28:54.310 align:middle line:84%
>> I mean, when I
think about flow,

00:28:54.310 --> 00:28:58.180 align:middle line:84%
I would go as far as-- once
I understood what flow was

00:28:58.180 --> 00:29:01.450 align:middle line:84%
and then I kind of retroactively
looked back on my own life,

00:29:01.450 --> 00:29:07.360 align:middle line:84%
every significant moment in my
life, those archived memories,

00:29:07.360 --> 00:29:13.840 align:middle line:84%
those bookmarked moments
were flooded by flow, right?

00:29:13.840 --> 00:29:16.720 align:middle line:84%
You feel your best, and
you perform your best.

00:29:16.720 --> 00:29:19.390 align:middle line:84%
When you say near-perfect
decision-making,

00:29:19.390 --> 00:29:21.700 align:middle line:84%
that's when that really
resonated with me

00:29:21.700 --> 00:29:26.160 align:middle line:84%
in terms of when I make my
videos, which are not scripted.

00:29:26.160 --> 00:29:29.560 align:middle line:84%
They're very much freestyle,
or stream of consciousness,

00:29:29.560 --> 00:29:31.953 align:middle line:84%
or like following a
butterfly effect in thought.

00:29:31.953 --> 00:29:33.370 align:middle line:84%
So when you think
about the notion

00:29:33.370 --> 00:29:37.180 align:middle line:84%
of near-perfect decision-making,
when you're having a riff,

00:29:37.180 --> 00:29:38.378 align:middle line:90%
you're having a download.

00:29:38.378 --> 00:29:40.420 align:middle line:84%
You're having one of those
moments where it comes

00:29:40.420 --> 00:29:41.570 align:middle line:90%
through you, but not from you.

00:29:41.570 --> 00:29:43.487 align:middle line:84%
And though it is with
you, belongs not to you.

00:29:43.487 --> 00:29:47.230 align:middle line:84%
You're a vessel like the
freestyle rapper or the jazz

00:29:47.230 --> 00:29:48.400 align:middle line:90%
musician.

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:50.692 align:middle line:84%
And what happens is the
dorsolateral prefrontal cortex,

00:29:50.692 --> 00:29:51.492 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:29:51.492 --> 00:29:53.260 align:middle line:84%
The part-- the
self-editor in the brain,

00:29:53.260 --> 00:29:55.450 align:middle line:84%
the part that second
guesses and tells you no.

00:29:55.450 --> 00:29:57.040 align:middle line:90%
That goes quiet.

00:29:57.040 --> 00:29:59.230 align:middle line:84%
And so it's like you
get out of your own way.

00:29:59.230 --> 00:30:00.790 align:middle line:90%
It's not just a metaphor.

00:30:00.790 --> 00:30:03.550 align:middle line:84%
You literally step
aside from yourself.

00:30:03.550 --> 00:30:05.530 align:middle line:84%
But the near-perfect
decision-making part

00:30:05.530 --> 00:30:08.290 align:middle line:84%
is the part of
you that is seeing

00:30:08.290 --> 00:30:10.570 align:middle line:84%
how all the right
words are emerging

00:30:10.570 --> 00:30:13.840 align:middle line:84%
at just the right moment
like the movie, "Limitless,"

00:30:13.840 --> 00:30:15.190 align:middle line:90%
when the guy takes that drug.

00:30:15.190 --> 00:30:19.060 align:middle line:84%
And it's just like your pattern
recognition ability go up.

00:30:19.060 --> 00:30:21.190 align:middle line:84%
But you're at just
the right speed

00:30:21.190 --> 00:30:22.960 align:middle line:84%
that you can surf
what's happening.

00:30:22.960 --> 00:30:27.640 align:middle line:84%
So if ordinary life
is kind of flat water,

00:30:27.640 --> 00:30:32.230 align:middle line:84%
flow is like the perfect wave
that you can surf, not so

00:30:32.230 --> 00:30:33.830 align:middle line:90%
much that you're wiping out.

00:30:33.830 --> 00:30:36.760 align:middle line:84%
But it's just-- and you're
making just the right decisions

00:30:36.760 --> 00:30:40.120 align:middle line:84%
to stay perfectly on the wave
and deliver the perfect riff,

00:30:40.120 --> 00:30:41.980 align:middle line:90%
whatever that performance is.

00:30:41.980 --> 00:30:44.650 align:middle line:84%
And you're also
really enjoying it.

00:30:44.650 --> 00:30:46.520 align:middle line:90%
You're witnessing it happening.

00:30:46.520 --> 00:30:50.060 align:middle line:84%
You're witnessing yourself
letting it go through you.

00:30:50.060 --> 00:30:51.980 align:middle line:84%
And it's absolutely
exhilarating.

00:30:51.980 --> 00:30:54.710 align:middle line:84%
And then if you're smart
enough or lucky enough

00:30:54.710 --> 00:30:58.070 align:middle line:84%
to have that be happening
in a context of music,

00:30:58.070 --> 00:31:01.940 align:middle line:84%
or freestyle, or writing, so
that it's getting transcribed,

00:31:01.940 --> 00:31:02.780 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:31:02.780 --> 00:31:05.327 align:middle line:84%
And then when the
experience is over--

00:31:05.327 --> 00:31:07.160 align:middle line:84%
because again, it's a
transitory experience.

00:31:07.160 --> 00:31:09.070 align:middle line:90%
But then you have evidence.

00:31:09.070 --> 00:31:12.110 align:middle line:84%
You have a concrete thing
that came out of you, that you

00:31:12.110 --> 00:31:13.152 align:middle line:90%
had to put in a drawer.

00:31:13.152 --> 00:31:15.485 align:middle line:84%
And that's one of the most
deeply satisfying experiences

00:31:15.485 --> 00:31:16.370 align:middle line:90%
of my life.

00:31:16.370 --> 00:31:21.410 align:middle line:84%
Because I've taken ephemeral
ecstasy, and I've bottled it.

00:31:21.410 --> 00:31:25.353 align:middle line:84%
I've put a cloak around it, and
that's absolutely exhilarating.

00:31:25.353 --> 00:31:27.020 align:middle line:84%
So it's like-- you
said once that people

00:31:27.020 --> 00:31:29.740 align:middle line:84%
who discover how to get flow,
build their lives around it.

00:31:29.740 --> 00:31:31.490 align:middle line:84%
And those that build
their lives around it

00:31:31.490 --> 00:31:34.050 align:middle line:84%
report the highest levels of
life satisfaction of any group,

00:31:34.050 --> 00:31:34.940 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:31:34.940 --> 00:31:37.160 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, which is very true.

00:31:37.160 --> 00:31:40.530 align:middle line:84%
It's worth taking that one step
back, because it's more useful.

00:31:40.530 --> 00:31:45.980 align:middle line:84%
So what we've discovered over
the past 10 years, 12 years--

00:31:45.980 --> 00:31:48.993 align:middle line:84%
and I've been involved
in this research.

00:31:48.993 --> 00:31:51.410 align:middle line:84%
A lot of other people have
been involved in this research.

00:31:51.410 --> 00:31:52.880 align:middle line:84%
But we figured out
that flow states

00:31:52.880 --> 00:31:56.150 align:middle line:84%
have triggers, pre-conditions
that lead to more flow.

00:31:56.150 --> 00:31:59.600 align:middle line:84%
And for those of you
who speak science,

00:31:59.600 --> 00:32:01.580 align:middle line:84%
the triggers do one
of two things, really.

00:32:01.580 --> 00:32:04.442 align:middle line:84%
They either drive norepinephrine
and dopamine into the brain,

00:32:04.442 --> 00:32:05.650 align:middle line:90%
which are focusing chemicals.

00:32:05.650 --> 00:32:07.330 align:middle line:84%
So what they do
is drive attention

00:32:07.330 --> 00:32:08.810 align:middle line:90%
into the present moment.

00:32:08.810 --> 00:32:10.850 align:middle line:84%
Or they lower
cognitive load, which

00:32:10.850 --> 00:32:13.310 align:middle line:84%
means all the shit you're
trying to think about at once--

00:32:13.310 --> 00:32:14.390 align:middle line:90%
that kind of dials back.

00:32:14.390 --> 00:32:15.485 align:middle line:90%
And again, same effect.

00:32:15.485 --> 00:32:17.360 align:middle line:84%
You get to pay more
attention to the present.

00:32:17.360 --> 00:32:19.850 align:middle line:84%
The flow only shows up
when all our attention

00:32:19.850 --> 00:32:21.030 align:middle line:90%
is right here, right now.

00:32:21.030 --> 00:32:23.180 align:middle line:90%
Very task focused.

00:32:23.180 --> 00:32:27.050 align:middle line:84%
So what has happened is we now
know that those states have

00:32:27.050 --> 00:32:29.960 align:middle line:90%
20, 21, 22 different triggers.

00:32:29.960 --> 00:32:32.240 align:middle line:84%
And there's probably
way more, but that's

00:32:32.240 --> 00:32:34.310 align:middle line:90%
what we've discovered so far.

00:32:34.310 --> 00:32:36.870 align:middle line:84%
So the people who are
really good at this

00:32:36.870 --> 00:32:39.380 align:middle line:84%
and are people who basically
have built their lives

00:32:39.380 --> 00:32:41.720 align:middle line:90%
around all of these triggers--

00:32:41.720 --> 00:32:43.280 align:middle line:90%
you've done it inadvertently.

00:32:43.280 --> 00:32:45.697 align:middle line:84%
And that's actually like--
this leads me to an interesting

00:32:45.697 --> 00:32:46.670 align:middle line:90%
question, which is--

00:32:46.670 --> 00:32:49.340 align:middle line:84%
so if you read "Stealing
Fire" from me with that book,

00:32:49.340 --> 00:32:53.870 align:middle line:84%
at one point in the chapter
on flow, we write about Jason.

00:32:53.870 --> 00:32:56.840 align:middle line:84%
And we wrote about his
early childhood experiences

00:32:56.840 --> 00:33:01.100 align:middle line:84%
in Venezuela and using
freestyle philosophy as a way

00:33:01.100 --> 00:33:06.696 align:middle line:84%
to kind of fight PTSD of growing
up in a tragic situation.

00:33:06.696 --> 00:33:09.020 align:middle line:84%
So you were already
flow hacking back then.

00:33:09.020 --> 00:33:12.150 align:middle line:84%
What I want to know is, what
were you doing back then?

00:33:12.150 --> 00:33:14.550 align:middle line:90%
And how has it changed to now?

00:33:14.550 --> 00:33:16.800 align:middle line:84%
How has your process changed
in terms of [INAUDIBLE]??

00:33:16.800 --> 00:33:17.000 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:17.800 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:33:17.800 --> 00:33:23.800 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it was like being
present is very hard for me.

00:33:23.800 --> 00:33:25.110 align:middle line:90%
It's very hard.

00:33:25.110 --> 00:33:27.430 align:middle line:90%
I've tried meditation and yoga.

00:33:27.430 --> 00:33:31.180 align:middle line:84%
And my girlfriend is a
meditator and a yogi.

00:33:31.180 --> 00:33:35.710 align:middle line:84%
That might work for some
people if you try really hard,

00:33:35.710 --> 00:33:41.470 align:middle line:84%
but it's not a smooth entry
into the present or into flow.

00:33:41.470 --> 00:33:45.340 align:middle line:84%
Michael Pollan's book,
"How to Change your Mind--"

00:33:45.340 --> 00:33:47.080 align:middle line:90%
in the preface of the book--

00:33:47.080 --> 00:33:50.770 align:middle line:84%
describes kind of the
default human condition.

00:33:50.770 --> 00:33:54.070 align:middle line:84%
Here I thought I was the only
one struggling with this.

00:33:54.070 --> 00:33:57.820 align:middle line:84%
He says the brain is kind of
an artificial intelligence

00:33:57.820 --> 00:33:58.720 align:middle line:90%
program.

00:33:58.720 --> 00:34:01.090 align:middle line:84%
It takes in data
from the present,

00:34:01.090 --> 00:34:03.160 align:middle line:84%
compares that with
data from the past

00:34:03.160 --> 00:34:05.570 align:middle line:84%
and uses that to
predict the future.

00:34:05.570 --> 00:34:08.139 align:middle line:84%
The brain is essentially
a prediction machine.

00:34:08.139 --> 00:34:10.330 align:middle line:84%
And it's doing
that to protect you

00:34:10.330 --> 00:34:12.730 align:middle line:84%
from something unexpected
going around the bend.

00:34:12.730 --> 00:34:14.690 align:middle line:84%
You're mitigating
against future risk.

00:34:14.690 --> 00:34:17.620 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, thinking of
and planning for the future

00:34:17.620 --> 00:34:20.580 align:middle line:84%
also is responsible for
us being so successful.

00:34:20.580 --> 00:34:23.800 align:middle line:84%
So being in the present all the
time also means you get eaten.

00:34:23.800 --> 00:34:25.989 align:middle line:84%
Because the tiger behind
you comes running.

00:34:25.989 --> 00:34:27.219 align:middle line:84%
And you never saw it
coming, because you

00:34:27.219 --> 00:34:29.469 align:middle line:84%
were busy looking at the
flower that was so beautiful,

00:34:29.469 --> 00:34:31.900 align:middle line:90%
so there's a reason for that.

00:34:31.900 --> 00:34:34.690 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, he says
that our default

00:34:34.690 --> 00:34:38.380 align:middle line:84%
is one of living in a
perpetual future tense

00:34:38.380 --> 00:34:41.739 align:middle line:84%
with a low level of anxiety
that's always present.

00:34:41.739 --> 00:34:44.590 align:middle line:84%
And the good news is
I'm seldom surprised.

00:34:44.590 --> 00:34:48.110 align:middle line:84%
The bad news is I'm
seldom surprised.

00:34:48.110 --> 00:34:49.780 align:middle line:84%
And then he says that
one of the things

00:34:49.780 --> 00:34:55.210 align:middle line:84%
that commends
travel, art, beauty,

00:34:55.210 --> 00:34:57.250 align:middle line:90%
and certain kinds of drugs--

00:34:57.250 --> 00:34:59.410 align:middle line:90%
in my case, cannabis--

00:34:59.410 --> 00:35:04.450 align:middle line:84%
is that these experiences
block all signals,

00:35:04.450 --> 00:35:07.270 align:middle line:90%
forwards and backwards, right?

00:35:07.270 --> 00:35:10.170 align:middle line:84%
So it's the comparing this
with the past and predicting.

00:35:10.170 --> 00:35:15.950 align:middle line:84%
They just block, throwing you
into the present or the flow.

00:35:15.950 --> 00:35:18.940 align:middle line:84%
He writes the word
the flow, of a present

00:35:18.940 --> 00:35:22.510 align:middle line:90%
that is literally wonder full--

00:35:22.510 --> 00:35:23.560 align:middle line:90%
full of wonder.

00:35:23.560 --> 00:35:28.480 align:middle line:84%
Wonder being the byproduct
of exactly that unencumbered

00:35:28.480 --> 00:35:32.950 align:middle line:84%
sense of first sight or
virginal noticing to which

00:35:32.950 --> 00:35:35.830 align:middle line:84%
the adult mind
has closed itself.

00:35:35.830 --> 00:35:39.160 align:middle line:84%
So it's actually by inhibiting
our brains' capacity

00:35:39.160 --> 00:35:44.770 align:middle line:84%
to be pre-mapping the
future or living in or using

00:35:44.770 --> 00:35:47.500 align:middle line:84%
the past to taint what's
happening, to over-determine

00:35:47.500 --> 00:35:49.810 align:middle line:84%
what's happening
by inhibiting that,

00:35:49.810 --> 00:35:52.420 align:middle line:84%
by actually constraining
that capacity.

00:35:52.420 --> 00:35:56.030 align:middle line:84%
In pot, they call it the messing
with your short-term memory.

00:35:56.030 --> 00:35:57.730 align:middle line:84%
It actually ends up
being a good thing.

00:35:57.730 --> 00:36:00.910 align:middle line:84%
Because it offers us temporary
relief from a faculty

00:36:00.910 --> 00:36:04.100 align:middle line:84%
that evolved to keep
us safe, so to speak.

00:36:04.100 --> 00:36:07.490 align:middle line:84%
And we can finally become
innocent bystanders

00:36:07.490 --> 00:36:08.290 align:middle line:90%
in the present.

00:36:08.290 --> 00:36:10.090 align:middle line:90%
We can be as children.

00:36:10.090 --> 00:36:12.580 align:middle line:84%
And that infuses the world
with a sense of wonder.

00:36:12.580 --> 00:36:15.550 align:middle line:84%
And then anything that enters
our field of consciousness

00:36:15.550 --> 00:36:18.010 align:middle line:84%
in that moment of
hyper-presence--

00:36:18.010 --> 00:36:21.490 align:middle line:84%
God, it becomes rich
material for engagement.

00:36:21.490 --> 00:36:25.900 align:middle line:84%
So if you're in nature, if
