So I lit out on a giant
quest to figure out

00:44:38.630 --> 00:44:39.838 align:middle line:90%
what the hell happened to me.

00:44:39.838 --> 00:44:41.780 align:middle line:90%
And what I quickly learned--

00:44:41.780 --> 00:44:42.800 align:middle line:90%
not quickly.

00:44:42.800 --> 00:44:43.910 align:middle line:90%
It took years.

00:44:43.910 --> 00:44:46.250 align:middle line:84%
But Herb Benson,
cardiologist at Harvard,

00:44:46.250 --> 00:44:47.900 align:middle line:90%
did a lot of this work.

00:44:47.900 --> 00:44:51.740 align:middle line:84%
He mapped the neurochemical
cycle underneath flow.

00:44:51.740 --> 00:44:56.810 align:middle line:84%
And what he pointed out is
that when we go into flow,

00:44:56.810 --> 00:44:58.290 align:middle line:90%
you reset the nervous system.

00:44:58.290 --> 00:45:00.710 align:middle line:84%
So Lyme disease-- any
autoimmune condition

00:45:00.710 --> 00:45:02.960 align:middle line:84%
is a nervous system
gone haywire.

00:45:02.960 --> 00:45:04.700 align:middle line:84%
And when you go
into flow, there's

00:45:04.700 --> 00:45:07.160 align:middle line:84%
a global release of a
chemical called nitrous oxide.

00:45:07.160 --> 00:45:09.590 align:middle line:84%
And it basically throws
all the stress hormones out

00:45:09.590 --> 00:45:13.865 align:middle line:84%
of your system and fills you
with feel-good neurochemistry.

00:45:13.865 --> 00:45:14.930 align:middle line:90%
>> Create nitrous oxide?

00:45:14.930 --> 00:45:15.730 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:45:15.730 --> 00:45:16.980 align:middle line:90%
That gas is a single molecule.

00:45:16.980 --> 00:45:18.670 align:middle line:90%
It's everywhere in your body.

00:45:18.670 --> 00:45:21.170 align:middle line:84%
They're not in a lot of gases--
small molecules in the body.

00:45:21.170 --> 00:45:24.350 align:middle line:90%
But that's one of them.

00:45:24.350 --> 00:45:25.400 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, we're geeks.

00:45:25.400 --> 00:45:26.780 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:26.780 --> 00:45:28.620 align:middle line:90%


00:45:28.620 --> 00:45:30.890 align:middle line:84%
But all those neurochemicals
besides resetting

00:45:30.890 --> 00:45:33.170 align:middle line:84%
the immune system, which is
amazingly powerful if you

00:45:33.170 --> 00:45:34.970 align:middle line:90%
have an autoimmune condition.

00:45:34.970 --> 00:45:36.425 align:middle line:84%
And Herb Benson
has gone so far as

00:45:36.425 --> 00:45:38.300 align:middle line:84%
to say he thinks this
is the mechanism that's

00:45:38.300 --> 00:45:40.910 align:middle line:84%
underneath most so-called
cases of spontaneous healing.

00:45:40.910 --> 00:45:42.800 align:middle line:84%
It's either placebo
effect or flow

00:45:42.800 --> 00:45:44.300 align:middle line:84%
that's pretty much
producing that as

00:45:44.300 --> 00:45:46.325 align:middle line:90%
far as science can tell.

00:45:46.325 --> 00:45:48.200 align:middle line:84%
Obviously, there might
be other explanations.

00:45:48.200 --> 00:45:49.740 align:middle line:84%
But from a scientific
perspective,

00:45:49.740 --> 00:45:51.306 align:middle line:90%
that's what we know.

00:45:51.306 --> 00:45:54.230 align:middle line:84%
And the other thing is all
those neurochemicals massively

00:45:54.230 --> 00:45:55.515 align:middle line:90%
boost the immune system.

00:45:55.515 --> 00:45:57.140 align:middle line:84%
So you're resetting
the nervous system.

00:45:57.140 --> 00:45:59.490 align:middle line:84%
You're massively boosting
the immune system.

00:45:59.490 --> 00:46:02.535 align:middle line:84%
And over a period
of time, I went--

00:46:02.535 --> 00:46:03.410 align:middle line:90%
I got back to health.

00:46:03.410 --> 00:46:05.720 align:middle line:84%
So that's the story
he's referring to.

00:46:05.720 --> 00:46:08.770 align:middle line:84%
And there was a
second part of that.

00:46:08.770 --> 00:46:09.570 align:middle line:90%
What else?

00:46:09.570 --> 00:46:10.060 align:middle line:90%
Where did--

00:46:10.060 --> 00:46:10.940 align:middle line:90%
>> No, just--

00:46:10.940 --> 00:46:11.857 align:middle line:90%
>> --you go with that?

00:46:11.857 --> 00:46:14.500 align:middle line:84%
>> [INAUDIBLE] that
flow also has a price,

00:46:14.500 --> 00:46:17.980 align:middle line:84%
and that you have flow cycles,
and that these experiences can

00:46:17.980 --> 00:46:19.330 align:middle line:90%
be addicting.

00:46:19.330 --> 00:46:23.920 align:middle line:84%
You could say that flow is the
most addictive state on Earth.

00:46:23.920 --> 00:46:26.710 align:middle line:84%
And so it's like, how
do you work around it?

00:46:26.710 --> 00:46:30.160 align:middle line:84%
How do you mitigate
the crash from flow?

00:46:30.160 --> 00:46:33.010 align:middle line:90%
How do you rest and recuperate?

00:46:33.010 --> 00:46:35.950 align:middle line:90%
And how do you avoid crashing?

00:46:35.950 --> 00:46:38.470 align:middle line:84%
And also, what's the role
of sleep in recuperating?

00:46:38.470 --> 00:46:40.720 align:middle line:84%
And also, what's the
quickest shortcut to flow?

00:46:40.720 --> 00:46:42.670 align:middle line:84%
You once called it
the hippie speed ball,

00:46:42.670 --> 00:46:45.730 align:middle line:84%
which was 20 minutes of aerobic
exercise, a shot of espresso,

00:46:45.730 --> 00:46:46.690 align:middle line:90%
and a joint.

00:46:46.690 --> 00:46:47.633 align:middle line:90%
>> Sativa.

00:46:47.633 --> 00:46:48.550 align:middle line:90%
It's got to be sativa.

00:46:48.550 --> 00:46:49.940 align:middle line:84%
You need dopamine
on the front end.

00:46:49.940 --> 00:46:50.110 align:middle line:90%
>> Sativa.

00:46:50.110 --> 00:46:50.540 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:46:50.540 --> 00:46:51.608 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, he's right.

00:46:51.608 --> 00:46:53.650 align:middle line:84%
Mimics all of the
neurochemcals or a lot of them.

00:46:53.650 --> 00:46:56.300 align:middle line:90%
It's very close to flow.

00:46:56.300 --> 00:46:59.090 align:middle line:84%
So let's start with
sleep, cause sleep--

00:46:59.090 --> 00:46:59.890 align:middle line:90%
so let's first--

00:46:59.890 --> 00:47:02.948 align:middle line:84%
>> My friends make fun of me for
how much I treasure my sleep.

00:47:02.948 --> 00:47:04.990 align:middle line:84%
>> Oh, but you and I are
the-- we're the same way

00:47:04.990 --> 00:47:05.990 align:middle line:90%
and for the same reason.

00:47:05.990 --> 00:47:08.510 align:middle line:84%
So let's start with
what he's referring to,

00:47:08.510 --> 00:47:09.833 align:middle line:90%
so you guys can understand it.

00:47:09.833 --> 00:47:11.250 align:middle line:84%
He's not kidding
when he says flow

00:47:11.250 --> 00:47:14.230 align:middle line:84%
is the most addictive state
on Earth neurochemically.

00:47:14.230 --> 00:47:16.990 align:middle line:84%
So we have endogenous
neurochemicals.

00:47:16.990 --> 00:47:18.460 align:middle line:90%
We make endorphins.

00:47:18.460 --> 00:47:20.380 align:middle line:90%
And we have exogenous chemicals.

00:47:20.380 --> 00:47:22.480 align:middle line:90%
Opiates are endorphins, right?

00:47:22.480 --> 00:47:24.570 align:middle line:90%
We make our own version of them.

00:47:24.570 --> 00:47:26.350 align:middle line:84%
And to put it in
perspective, there

00:47:26.350 --> 00:47:29.240 align:middle line:84%
are about 20 different
endorphins in the body.

00:47:29.240 --> 00:47:31.870 align:middle line:84%
The most common one is a
hundred times more potent

00:47:31.870 --> 00:47:33.460 align:middle line:90%
than medical morphine.

00:47:33.460 --> 00:47:36.320 align:middle line:90%
Dopamine is cocaine.

00:47:36.320 --> 00:47:38.230 align:middle line:84%
And literally, when
people snort cocaine,

00:47:38.230 --> 00:47:40.600 align:middle line:84%
the most addictive substance
on Earth, all that happens

00:47:40.600 --> 00:47:43.030 align:middle line:90%
is the brain releases dopamine.

00:47:43.030 --> 00:47:46.870 align:middle line:84%
It's a signaling molecule,
and it blocks its reuptake.

00:47:46.870 --> 00:47:48.850 align:middle line:84%
Serotonin, which also
shows up in flow,

00:47:48.850 --> 00:47:50.350 align:middle line:84%
depending on which
pathway it takes,

00:47:50.350 --> 00:47:52.105 align:middle line:90%
it's either MDMA or ecstasy.

00:47:52.105 --> 00:47:54.715 align:middle line:84%
You get norepinephrine,
and that is crystal meth.

00:47:54.715 --> 00:47:57.570 align:middle line:84%
It's one methyl chain
away from a crystal meth.

00:47:57.570 --> 00:48:00.430 align:middle line:84%
Street speed is the
natural version.

00:48:00.430 --> 00:48:03.460 align:middle line:84%
You couldn't-- and anandamide,
which is the same psychoactive

00:48:03.460 --> 00:48:05.623 align:middle line:84%
that shows up in marijuana--
it's what THC releases

00:48:05.623 --> 00:48:06.820 align:middle line:90%
in the brain.

00:48:06.820 --> 00:48:09.280 align:middle line:84%
You couldn't cocktail
those drugs on the street.

00:48:09.280 --> 00:48:10.700 align:middle line:90%
You'd end up in a coma.

00:48:10.700 --> 00:48:11.500 align:middle line:90%
They wouldn't work.

00:48:11.500 --> 00:48:14.455 align:middle line:84%
You actually can't-- cocaine
and ecstasy won't work together.

00:48:14.455 --> 00:48:15.580 align:middle line:90%
They cancel each other out.

00:48:15.580 --> 00:48:18.250 align:middle line:84%
So you couldn't even
do it if you tried.

00:48:18.250 --> 00:48:20.020 align:middle line:90%
Flow does it naturally.

00:48:20.020 --> 00:48:22.510 align:middle line:84%
This is the most potent
chemical anywhere.

00:48:22.510 --> 00:48:25.180 align:middle line:84%
Just to put it in comparison,
romantic love-- and we

00:48:25.180 --> 00:48:26.860 align:middle line:90%
all know how good that feels.

00:48:26.860 --> 00:48:27.910 align:middle line:90%
That's two chemicals.

00:48:27.910 --> 00:48:29.710 align:middle line:84%
That's norepinephrine
and dopamine.

00:48:29.710 --> 00:48:32.050 align:middle line:84%
Flow is five of these
chemicals-- most

00:48:32.050 --> 00:48:33.100 align:middle line:90%
addictive state on Earth.

00:48:33.100 --> 00:48:34.900 align:middle line:90%
And what we've learned--

00:48:34.900 --> 00:48:37.060 align:middle line:84%
this is, again, Herbert
Benson's work at Harvard,

00:48:37.060 --> 00:48:38.560 align:middle line:84%
who did the
foundational work, is we

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:39.790 align:middle line:90%
used to think flow is a binary.

00:48:39.790 --> 00:48:42.070 align:middle line:84%
You're in the zone, you're
not, you're out of the zone.

00:48:42.070 --> 00:48:43.820 align:middle line:84%
And we now know it
doesn't work like that.

00:48:43.820 --> 00:48:45.350 align:middle line:90%
It's a four-stage cycle.

00:48:45.350 --> 00:48:48.380 align:middle line:84%
And you have to move all
the way through all stages.

00:48:48.380 --> 00:48:50.383 align:middle line:84%
But once a month or so,
somebody comes up to me

00:48:50.383 --> 00:48:52.120 align:middle line:84%
and says, oh, Steven,
you've got to study me.

00:48:52.120 --> 00:48:53.200 align:middle line:90%
I'm in flow all the time.

00:48:53.200 --> 00:48:54.604 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:54.604 --> 00:48:54.933 align:middle line:90%


00:48:54.933 --> 00:48:57.100 align:middle line:84%
And in the beginning when
that used to happen to me,

00:48:57.100 --> 00:48:58.510 align:middle line:84%
I'd be like, oh, I
don't know if I should

00:48:58.510 --> 00:48:59.552 align:middle line:90%
tell this dude the truth.

00:48:59.552 --> 00:49:00.700 align:middle line:90%
But now, I just say it.

00:49:00.700 --> 00:49:02.780 align:middle line:84%
I'm like, we have
a word for that.

00:49:02.780 --> 00:49:03.940 align:middle line:90%
We call that schizophrenia.

00:49:03.940 --> 00:49:04.800 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:04.800 --> 00:49:05.600 align:middle line:90%


00:49:05.600 --> 00:49:06.670 align:middle line:90%
So, yeah.

00:49:06.670 --> 00:49:09.017 align:middle line:84%
You don't get to actually
live in flow all the time.

00:49:09.017 --> 00:49:10.600 align:middle line:84%
So anybody who's
running around going,

00:49:10.600 --> 00:49:13.060 align:middle line:84%
dude, I'm in flow
all the time, yeah,

00:49:13.060 --> 00:49:15.940 align:middle line:84%
you're a manic depressive who
should probably see a doctor.

00:49:15.940 --> 00:49:18.610 align:middle line:90%


00:49:18.610 --> 00:49:21.670 align:middle line:84%
But the point is that
when we go into flow,

00:49:21.670 --> 00:49:24.250 align:middle line:84%
it is a neural chemically
expensive state.

00:49:24.250 --> 00:49:27.100 align:middle line:84%
And these chemicals are
short lived-- some of them.

00:49:27.100 --> 00:49:30.250 align:middle line:84%
Norepinephrine and dopamine,
the romantic love chemicals,

00:49:30.250 --> 00:49:32.110 align:middle line:84%
are also your main
focusing chemicals.

00:49:32.110 --> 00:49:34.178 align:middle line:84%
Why are TED Talks
20 minutes long?

00:49:34.178 --> 00:49:36.220 align:middle line:84%
Because they last about
20 minutes in your brain.

00:49:36.220 --> 00:49:38.457 align:middle line:84%
That's how long we can
focus really intensely,

00:49:38.457 --> 00:49:39.790 align:middle line:90%
and then it starts to fade away.

00:49:39.790 --> 00:49:40.750 align:middle line:90%
We've all had this experience.

00:49:40.750 --> 00:49:42.250 align:middle line:84%
You see in the
"James Bond" movie.

00:49:42.250 --> 00:49:44.410 align:middle line:84%
Everything blows up for
the first 20 minutes.

00:49:44.410 --> 00:49:46.600 align:middle line:84%
And then you're bored for
the next hour and a half.

00:49:46.600 --> 00:49:48.550 align:middle line:84%
You're bored because
those explosions

00:49:48.550 --> 00:49:50.680 align:middle line:84%
have stolen all your
dopamine and norepinephrine.

00:49:50.680 --> 00:49:53.260 align:middle line:84%
And you can no
longer focus at all.

00:49:53.260 --> 00:49:55.000 align:middle line:84%
That's what's going
on in your brain.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:57.190 align:middle line:84%
So on the back end
of a flow state,

00:49:57.190 --> 00:49:59.410 align:middle line:84%
big, high,
neurochemically expensive.

00:49:59.410 --> 00:50:01.090 align:middle line:90%
There's a crash, right?

00:50:01.090 --> 00:50:02.470 align:middle line:90%
It's a recovery phase.

00:50:02.470 --> 00:50:06.460 align:middle line:84%
And actually, I think--
and other scientists

00:50:06.460 --> 00:50:08.860 align:middle line:84%
and researchers have
kind of pointed at this.

00:50:08.860 --> 00:50:10.660 align:middle line:90%
We need much more experiments.

00:50:10.660 --> 00:50:12.010 align:middle line:90%
But flow is a really big high.

00:50:12.010 --> 00:50:14.840 align:middle line:84%
And I said it was near perfect,
not perfect decision-making.

00:50:14.840 --> 00:50:16.600 align:middle line:90%
It's followed by a deep low.

00:50:16.600 --> 00:50:19.600 align:middle line:84%
This may actually be
a refractory period.

00:50:19.600 --> 00:50:21.250 align:middle line:90%
You had all these great ideas.

00:50:21.250 --> 00:50:23.770 align:middle line:84%
And now, you get to look
at them very, very soberly.

00:50:23.770 --> 00:50:26.410 align:middle line:90%
I love-- I like writing in flow.

00:50:26.410 --> 00:50:28.010 align:middle line:90%
I love editing on the back end.

00:50:28.010 --> 00:50:30.350 align:middle line:84%
Because if I like what I
wrote on the back end of it,

00:50:30.350 --> 00:50:32.410 align:middle line:84%
I've got no more
feel-good neurochemistry.

00:50:32.410 --> 00:50:36.130 align:middle line:84%
Shit's got to be good, because
I'm grumpy as hell, right?

00:50:36.130 --> 00:50:39.380 align:middle line:84%
So it works to your benefit
if you know how to use it.

00:50:39.380 --> 00:50:41.030 align:middle line:90%
So that's why.

00:50:41.030 --> 00:50:43.392 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, that works for
when I do my videos, too.

00:50:43.392 --> 00:50:44.600 align:middle line:90%
>> And it's why sleep is so--

00:50:44.600 --> 00:50:44.930 align:middle line:90%
>> I've got a certain--

00:50:44.930 --> 00:50:45.730 align:middle line:90%
>> --important.

00:50:45.730 --> 00:50:47.560 align:middle line:90%
>> --level of peak flow.

00:50:47.560 --> 00:50:49.510 align:middle line:84%
And then I sometimes
record then.

00:50:49.510 --> 00:50:52.360 align:middle line:84%
But sometimes I record a
little bit in the afterglow.

00:50:52.360 --> 00:50:53.470 align:middle line:90%
Before, I fully crashed.

00:50:53.470 --> 00:50:55.660 align:middle line:84%
But I'm already kind of
starting to wind down, because--

00:50:55.660 --> 00:50:56.493 align:middle line:90%
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:50:56.493 --> 00:50:59.350 align:middle line:84%
And then I'll watch them
when I'm completely done.

00:50:59.350 --> 00:51:00.370 align:middle line:90%
>> You want more flow?

00:51:00.370 --> 00:51:02.200 align:middle line:84%
That's one of the worst
things you can do.

00:51:02.200 --> 00:51:03.200 align:middle line:90%
And I'll tell you why.

00:51:03.200 --> 00:51:05.580 align:middle line:84%
So we've all had
this experience.

00:51:05.580 --> 00:51:06.765 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:06.765 --> 00:51:07.128 align:middle line:90%


00:51:07.128 --> 00:51:09.420 align:middle line:84%
You get into a flow state,
and your ideas are spinning.

00:51:09.420 --> 00:51:10.140 align:middle line:90%
And you're like, oh, my God.

00:51:10.140 --> 00:51:11.610 align:middle line:90%
I've accessed all these ideas.

00:51:11.610 --> 00:51:13.830 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to follow them
out-- every last little one.

00:51:13.830 --> 00:51:15.240 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to catch all of them.

00:51:15.240 --> 00:51:16.440 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:51:16.440 --> 00:51:17.970 align:middle line:84%
And we're greedy
for those ideas.

00:51:17.970 --> 00:51:20.070 align:middle line:84%
And what happens is
by chasing them out,

00:51:20.070 --> 00:51:22.020 align:middle line:84%
you're exhausting
all your dopamine,

00:51:22.020 --> 00:51:23.900 align:middle line:84%
and you have nothing
to build with.

00:51:23.900 --> 00:51:24.700 align:middle line:90%
So--

00:51:24.700 --> 00:51:25.867 align:middle line:90%
>> I've had that experience.

00:51:25.867 --> 00:51:28.590 align:middle line:84%
>> --this is why Hemingway--
and I learned it from Gabriel

00:51:28.590 --> 00:51:29.750 align:middle line:90%
García Márquez.

00:51:29.750 --> 00:51:33.960 align:middle line:84%
But both Hemingway and Márquez
taught writers to quit when

00:51:33.960 --> 00:51:35.310 align:middle line:90%
you're most excited.

00:51:35.310 --> 00:51:38.610 align:middle line:84%
How do you get up and write
the best the next day?

00:51:38.610 --> 00:51:40.110 align:middle line:90%
Quit while you're most excited.

00:51:40.110 --> 00:51:42.810 align:middle line:84%
Usually by the time you've
noticed you're most excited,

00:51:42.810 --> 00:51:44.670 align:middle line:84%
it's on the tail
end of a flow state,

00:51:44.670 --> 00:51:47.640 align:middle line:84%
and you're going to be-- you're
moving downhill from there.

00:51:47.640 --> 00:51:49.170 align:middle line:90%
So I sort of do the same thing.

00:51:49.170 --> 00:51:51.030 align:middle line:84%
I get to a certain
point now in flow.

00:51:51.030 --> 00:51:54.030 align:middle line:84%
And the idea is really spiraling
where I decide I cut it off.

00:51:54.030 --> 00:51:55.260 align:middle line:90%
I do something intentionally.

00:51:55.260 --> 00:51:57.220 align:middle line:84%
I'll do something that
I never really do,

00:51:57.220 --> 00:51:59.850 align:middle line:84%
like I'll watch television
to just like-- it will

00:51:59.850 --> 00:52:01.480 align:middle line:90%
stop my brain from doing that.

00:52:01.480 --> 00:52:02.280 align:middle line:90%
>> Interesting.

00:52:02.280 --> 00:52:03.300 align:middle line:84%
>> Because I don't
want to exhaust it,

00:52:03.300 --> 00:52:05.160 align:middle line:84%
because I need more
flow the next day.

00:52:05.160 --> 00:52:07.090 align:middle line:84%
Because I'm a creative, and
I have to write every day.

00:52:07.090 --> 00:52:07.400 align:middle line:90%
>> Of course.

00:52:07.400 --> 00:52:09.263 align:middle line:84%
>> So that's how
I've messed with it.

00:52:09.263 --> 00:52:10.680 align:middle line:84%
So those are some
tips and tricks.

00:52:10.680 --> 00:52:11.480 align:middle line:90%
>> Excellent.

00:52:11.480 --> 00:52:14.190 align:middle line:84%
>> Oh, one other
thing about sleep.

00:52:14.190 --> 00:52:16.410 align:middle line:84%
Sleep is obviously
foundational for recovery,

00:52:16.410 --> 00:52:18.870 align:middle line:90%
and you can't cheat it, right?

00:52:18.870 --> 00:52:22.050 align:middle line:84%
Study after study shows we need
seven to eight hours a night.

00:52:22.050 --> 00:52:24.300 align:middle line:90%
There's no real way around it.

00:52:24.300 --> 00:52:27.630 align:middle line:84%
Nobody really does better with
less for long periods of time.

00:52:27.630 --> 00:52:30.662 align:middle line:84%
Interestingly, if you
don't have enough sleep,

00:52:30.662 --> 00:52:32.370 align:middle line:84%
it's really difficult
to get in the flow,

00:52:32.370 --> 00:52:34.200 align:middle line:84%
because it's a
high-energy state.

00:52:34.200 --> 00:52:38.040 align:middle line:84%
So you need lots of sleep to
maintain the focus, right?

00:52:38.040 --> 00:52:40.740 align:middle line:84%
To have specific focus
is expensive to do.

00:52:40.740 --> 00:52:43.332 align:middle line:84%
The brain doesn't
like to do it a lot.

00:52:43.332 --> 00:52:44.540 align:middle line:90%
>> That makes a lot of sense.

00:52:44.540 --> 00:52:47.170 align:middle line:90%
That's why I treasure my sleep.

00:52:47.170 --> 00:52:48.420 align:middle line:90%
So that's flow.

00:52:48.420 --> 00:52:51.660 align:middle line:84%
And if we learn to
master flow, that's

00:52:51.660 --> 00:52:55.920 align:middle line:84%
a great tool in
our toolkit that we

00:52:55.920 --> 00:52:58.830 align:middle line:84%
can leverage to boost
performance and make better

00:52:58.830 --> 00:53:02.010 align:middle line:84%
decisions, so that we can use
these tools and technologies we

00:53:02.010 --> 00:53:04.750 align:middle line:84%
were talking before to impact
the world in a positive way,

00:53:04.750 --> 00:53:06.800 align:middle line:90%
because we are the gods now.

00:53:06.800 --> 00:53:08.550 align:middle line:84%
I'd like to talk a
little bit about what's

00:53:08.550 --> 00:53:10.560 align:middle line:84%
happening with kind of
psychedelic research

00:53:10.560 --> 00:53:11.730 align:middle line:90%
for healing ourselves.

00:53:11.730 --> 00:53:15.255 align:middle line:90%
So people are dying from trauma.

00:53:15.255 --> 00:53:16.380 align:middle line:90%
They're killing themselves.

00:53:16.380 --> 00:53:19.140 align:middle line:84%
PTSD people have very
high suicide rates,

00:53:19.140 --> 00:53:20.160 align:middle line:90%
depression, anxiety.

00:53:20.160 --> 00:53:22.950 align:middle line:84%
People have treatment-resistant
depression and anxiety.

00:53:22.950 --> 00:53:23.888 align:middle line:90%
People are a mess.

00:53:23.888 --> 00:53:26.430 align:middle line:84%
And some of the most interesting
research happening right now

00:53:26.430 --> 00:53:30.090 align:middle line:84%
at places like Imperial College
of London, Johns Hopkins

00:53:30.090 --> 00:53:33.110 align:middle line:84%
University, NYU,
and other places

00:53:33.110 --> 00:53:35.613 align:middle line:84%
are they're creating these
controlled environments.

00:53:35.613 --> 00:53:38.280 align:middle line:84%
And they're bringing people with
treatment-resistant depression,

00:53:38.280 --> 00:53:40.740 align:middle line:90%
end of life, anxiety, PTSD.

00:53:40.740 --> 00:53:43.440 align:middle line:84%
And they're deploying these
ecstatic technologies.

00:53:43.440 --> 00:53:45.690 align:middle line:90%
They're using things like MDMA.

00:53:45.690 --> 00:53:47.400 align:middle line:84%
They're using things
like psilocybin

00:53:47.400 --> 00:53:48.960 align:middle line:90%
from magic mushrooms.

00:53:48.960 --> 00:53:52.140 align:middle line:84%
And in a very safe container,
they're essentially

00:53:52.140 --> 00:53:55.050 align:middle line:90%
inducing a mystical experience.

00:53:55.050 --> 00:53:57.750 align:middle line:84%
Now, a mystical experience
has to meet certain criteria,

00:53:57.750 --> 00:53:59.850 align:middle line:84%
according to William
James, the psychologist who

00:53:59.850 --> 00:54:02.380 align:middle line:84%
first created the questionnaire
of a mystical experience.

00:54:02.380 --> 00:54:04.260 align:middle line:84%
But what's interesting
is that it's not

00:54:04.260 --> 00:54:06.540 align:middle line:84%
the chemistry of
the drugs themselves

00:54:06.540 --> 00:54:10.000 align:middle line:84%
that seems to be responsible
for the healing that occurs,

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:12.940 align:middle line:84%
but it's the experience
that they can occasion.

00:54:12.940 --> 00:54:16.920 align:middle line:84%
So if a person has a full-on
mystical experience that

00:54:16.920 --> 00:54:19.652 align:middle line:84%
meets all the criteria, a
sense of interconnectedness,

00:54:19.652 --> 00:54:22.740 align:middle line:84%
a sense of transcendence
of time and space,

00:54:22.740 --> 00:54:25.530 align:middle line:84%
a sense of deep well being,
a sense of noetic truth

00:54:25.530 --> 00:54:28.800 align:middle line:84%
like a deeper spiritual
truth and day-to-day reality,

00:54:28.800 --> 00:54:30.690 align:middle line:84%
a sense of
paradoxicality where they

00:54:30.690 --> 00:54:32.485 align:middle line:84%
can hold multiple
truths in mind at once,

00:54:32.485 --> 00:54:34.860 align:middle line:84%
a sense that they transcend
their ego-- all these things.

00:54:34.860 --> 00:54:37.500 align:middle line:84%
If you have all those things,
if the contents of consciousness

00:54:37.500 --> 00:54:41.190 align:middle line:84%
play out and you have this
experience, this ego death,

00:54:41.190 --> 00:54:43.980 align:middle line:84%
this transcendence of
self, whatever that may be,

00:54:43.980 --> 00:54:47.640 align:middle line:84%
when you come out on
the other side of that,

00:54:47.640 --> 00:54:50.040 align:middle line:84%
enormously large
percentage of the people

00:54:50.040 --> 00:54:53.490 align:middle line:84%
no longer meet the
criteria for PTSD,

00:54:53.490 --> 00:54:55.050 align:middle line:90%
or depression, or anxiety.

00:54:55.050 --> 00:54:56.940 align:middle line:84%
A single psilocybin
trip can cure

00:54:56.940 --> 00:55:00.050 align:middle line:84%
somebody of multi-year
treatment-resistant depression.

00:55:00.050 --> 00:55:03.530 align:middle line:84%
A single-- I think two
or three MDMA sessions--

00:55:03.530 --> 00:55:08.700 align:middle line:84%
80% of the patients no longer
met the criteria for PTSD.

00:55:08.700 --> 00:55:11.520 align:middle line:84%
The head researcher at
Johns Hopkins University

00:55:11.520 --> 00:55:13.710 align:middle line:84%
likened these
mystical experience

00:55:13.710 --> 00:55:16.920 align:middle line:90%
as a kind of inverse PTSD.

00:55:16.920 --> 00:55:21.840 align:middle line:84%
So if you think of us as
the sum of our experiences

00:55:21.840 --> 00:55:25.050 align:middle line:84%
or ourselves as the technology
that turns experience

00:55:25.050 --> 00:55:29.160 align:middle line:84%
into biology, we are
what happens to us.

00:55:29.160 --> 00:55:34.500 align:middle line:84%
And so of course, trauma is
embedded in your physiology.

00:55:34.500 --> 00:55:36.380 align:middle line:90%
It becomes a lens of perception.

00:55:36.380 --> 00:55:39.150 align:middle line:84%
It's a past that doesn't
stay in the past.

00:55:39.150 --> 00:55:42.060 align:middle line:84%
And you bring it with you to
every moment-- your traumas,

00:55:42.060 --> 00:55:43.240 align:middle line:90%
your fears.

00:55:43.240 --> 00:55:45.990 align:middle line:84%
But an experience
of outrageous beauty

00:55:45.990 --> 00:55:48.050 align:middle line:90%
can do the inverse of that.

00:55:48.050 --> 00:55:51.540 align:middle line:84%
An experience of mystical
rapture, poetic reveries,

00:55:51.540 --> 00:55:53.540 align:middle line:90%
whatever.

00:55:53.540 --> 00:55:55.770 align:middle line:84%
The ontological truth
of these experiences

00:55:55.770 --> 00:56:00.270 align:middle line:84%
matters less if the experience
is meaningful to you,

00:56:00.270 --> 00:56:03.990 align:middle line:84%
meaningful enough to feel like
you have gone above and beyond

00:56:03.990 --> 00:56:06.090 align:middle line:90%
that which ailed you before.

00:56:06.090 --> 00:56:11.020 align:middle line:84%
Then it's a kind of inverse
PTSD that actually can heal us.

00:56:11.020 --> 00:56:13.180 align:middle line:84%
And people-- and there's
all this research, also,

00:56:13.180 --> 00:56:16.710 align:middle line:84%
on awe coming out of Berkeley
and all these other places.

00:56:16.710 --> 00:56:20.010 align:middle line:84%
And I think profound
cosmic awe is also

00:56:20.010 --> 00:56:22.510 align:middle line:84%
something people experience
when they have psychedelic trips

00:56:22.510 --> 00:56:23.890 align:middle line:90%
that are positive.

00:56:23.890 --> 00:56:26.733 align:middle line:84%
And awe is an experience of
such perceptual expansion

00:56:26.733 --> 00:56:28.150 align:middle line:84%
that your mental
models of reality

00:56:28.150 --> 00:56:31.120 align:middle line:84%
need to be upended to fit
in this new information,

00:56:31.120 --> 00:56:35.930 align:middle line:84%
to make space now for this
new truth, so to speak.

00:56:35.930 --> 00:56:39.220 align:middle line:84%
And that when you have
experiences of awe,

00:56:39.220 --> 00:56:42.010 align:middle line:84%
once they're over, you're left
with increased feelings of well

00:56:42.010 --> 00:56:43.690 align:middle line:84%
being, increased
feelings of compassion,

00:56:43.690 --> 00:56:45.670 align:middle line:84%
and increased feelings
of creativity.

00:56:45.670 --> 00:56:48.160 align:middle line:84%
And the experience is
anti-inflammatory in your body

00:56:48.160 --> 00:56:49.040 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:56:49.040 --> 00:56:52.750 align:middle line:84%
So this notion of deploying
these ecstatic technologies

00:56:52.750 --> 00:56:55.180 align:middle line:84%
in controlled,
responsible environments

00:56:55.180 --> 00:56:57.580 align:middle line:90%
and inducing these--

00:56:57.580 --> 00:56:58.480 align:middle line:90%
put a cord around it.

00:56:58.480 --> 00:57:02.260 align:middle line:84%
Spiritual experiences
heals people.

00:57:02.260 --> 00:57:05.230 align:middle line:84%
Now, I'm less interested in
the veracity of what occurred

00:57:05.230 --> 00:57:07.390 align:middle line:90%
inside the person's mind.

00:57:07.390 --> 00:57:09.010 align:middle line:90%
Christians will see Jesus.

00:57:09.010 --> 00:57:10.750 align:middle line:90%
Buddhists will see Buddha.

00:57:10.750 --> 00:57:14.020 align:middle line:84%
Nature lovers will see
the sacredness of nature.

00:57:14.020 --> 00:57:17.680 align:middle line:84%
The wallpaper-- you talked
about this in "Stealing Fire."

00:57:17.680 --> 00:57:19.720 align:middle line:90%
The wallpaper matters less.

00:57:19.720 --> 00:57:22.330 align:middle line:84%
Your cultural
constructions usually

00:57:22.330 --> 00:57:25.660 align:middle line:84%
will govern what you find
inside the psychedelic trip.

00:57:25.660 --> 00:57:27.640 align:middle line:84%
So I'm less interested
in the actual veracity

00:57:27.640 --> 00:57:28.510 align:middle line:90%
of your experience.

00:57:28.510 --> 00:57:28.650 align:middle line:90%
>> It's actually--

00:57:28.650 --> 00:57:28.990 align:middle line:90%
>> I'm only interested--

00:57:28.990 --> 00:57:29.823 align:middle line:90%
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:57:29.823 --> 00:57:31.310 align:middle line:84%
>> --If it was
meaningful to you.

00:57:31.310 --> 00:57:34.010 align:middle line:84%
And if it is, then we have
a moral responsibility,

00:57:34.010 --> 00:57:36.460 align:middle line:84%
I think, to create
psychedelic spas

00:57:36.460 --> 00:57:38.532 align:middle line:84%
and use these modalities
to heal people,

00:57:38.532 --> 00:57:39.740 align:middle line:90%
but I'll turn it over to you.

00:57:39.740 --> 00:57:42.668 align:middle line:84%
>> Oh, I was just going to get--
the one thing that I think is

00:57:42.668 --> 00:57:44.710 align:middle line:84%
really fascinating-- most
people don't know this,

00:57:44.710 --> 00:57:49.540 align:middle line:84%
is we only see four patterns
when we hallucinate.

00:57:49.540 --> 00:57:50.500 align:middle line:90%
And they're maps.

00:57:50.500 --> 00:57:51.400 align:middle line:90%
We see spirals.

00:57:51.400 --> 00:57:52.200 align:middle line:90%
We see lattices.

00:57:52.200 --> 00:57:54.010 align:middle line:90%
And they're all mapped onto--

00:57:54.010 --> 00:57:56.957 align:middle line:90%
so why do things spiral on acid?

00:57:56.957 --> 00:57:58.540 align:middle line:84%
When information
comes into the brain,

00:57:58.540 --> 00:57:59.832 align:middle line:90%
visual information goes to V1s.

00:57:59.832 --> 00:58:01.780 align:middle line:84%
The first level of
visual processing

00:58:01.780 --> 00:58:03.220 align:middle line:90%
does edge recognition.

00:58:03.220 --> 00:58:05.930 align:middle line:90%
It says this is a straight line.

00:58:05.930 --> 00:58:08.650 align:middle line:84%
This is right where this object
ends, and this object begins.

00:58:08.650 --> 00:58:11.890 align:middle line:84%
And if you can't do that,
things swirl together.

00:58:11.890 --> 00:58:14.180 align:middle line:84%
That's what the
swirling is on acid.

00:58:14.180 --> 00:58:16.820 align:middle line:84%
It's the breaking down of
edge recognition, if you want.

00:58:16.820 --> 00:58:18.110 align:middle line:90%
So I think that's fascinating.

00:58:18.110 --> 00:58:21.675 align:middle line:84%
But I want to expand
on what you said.

00:58:21.675 --> 00:58:23.050 align:middle line:84%
There's a reason
he poked at awe.

00:58:23.050 --> 00:58:24.300 align:middle line:90%
And he looked at psychedelics.

00:58:24.300 --> 00:58:27.970 align:middle line:84%
So what we know is
that roughly there's

00:58:27.970 --> 00:58:30.190 align:middle line:84%
differences, but
roughly the same.

00:58:30.190 --> 00:58:34.070 align:middle line:84%
William James pointed this
out way back in, I guess,

00:58:34.070 --> 00:58:35.510 align:middle line:84%
1902, when he
published "Varieties

00:58:35.510 --> 00:58:37.310 align:middle line:90%
of Religious Experiences."

00:58:37.310 --> 00:58:39.140 align:middle line:84%
He said two things
about all these.

00:58:39.140 --> 00:58:41.360 align:middle line:84%
He went around the world
looking at every kind

00:58:41.360 --> 00:58:43.020 align:middle line:84%
of mystical experience
he can find,

00:58:43.020 --> 00:58:45.080 align:middle line:84%
including a lot of
psychedelic experiences.

00:58:45.080 --> 00:58:49.010 align:middle line:84%
And it didn't matter kind
of what he looked at.

00:58:49.010 --> 00:58:51.232 align:middle line:84%
They all-- A, he said,
look, these things--

00:58:51.232 --> 00:58:52.940 align:middle line:84%
you can believe what
you want about them,

00:58:52.940 --> 00:58:54.560 align:middle line:84%
but they are
psychologically real.

00:58:54.560 --> 00:58:56.480 align:middle line:84%
On the other side of
these experiences,

00:58:56.480 --> 00:58:57.530 align:middle line:90%
people feel better.

00:58:57.530 --> 00:58:59.480 align:middle line:84%
They have better and
more meaningful lives,

00:58:59.480 --> 00:59:01.230 align:middle line:84%
and they heal trauma
and blah, blah, blah.

00:59:01.230 --> 00:59:02.480 align:middle line:90%
>> Psychologically real.

00:59:02.480 --> 00:59:03.750 align:middle line:90%
That's-- excellent term.

00:59:03.750 --> 00:59:04.550 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:59:04.550 --> 00:59:05.020 align:middle line:90%


00:59:05.020 --> 00:59:06.320 align:middle line:90%
No, because look, look, look.

00:59:06.320 --> 00:59:09.867 align:middle line:90%
We all want real real.

00:59:09.867 --> 00:59:11.450 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if you have
a psychedelic trip

00:59:11.450 --> 00:59:12.867 align:middle line:84%
and you have an
experience of what

00:59:12.867 --> 00:59:16.280 align:middle line:84%
you think God is, you
want it to be real real.

00:59:16.280 --> 00:59:17.930 align:middle line:90%
It's psychologically real.

00:59:17.930 --> 00:59:19.580 align:middle line:90%
But you want it to be real real.

00:59:19.580 --> 00:59:22.163 align:middle line:84%
Because that would be something
that you can put in a suitcase

00:59:22.163 --> 00:59:24.440 align:middle line:84%
and be like, oh, I
have the actual answer.

00:59:24.440 --> 00:59:26.660 align:middle line:84%
And unfortunately, it
doesn't feel like we can ever

00:59:26.660 --> 00:59:28.460 align:middle line:90%
know the real real.

00:59:28.460 --> 00:59:32.810 align:middle line:84%
But the psychologically real
can still be deeply meaningful.

00:59:32.810 --> 00:59:36.470 align:middle line:84%
I'm troubled by the
spiritual narcissism

00:59:36.470 --> 00:59:38.012 align:middle line:84%
or spiritual
fundamentalism of people

00:59:38.012 --> 00:59:40.345 align:middle line:84%
who have psychedelic experiences
and think that they are

00:59:40.345 --> 00:59:42.050 align:middle line:84%
the Messiah, that
the download they

00:59:42.050 --> 00:59:46.370 align:middle line:84%
got combined with their
cultural interpretation--

00:59:46.370 --> 00:59:48.290 align:middle line:84%
they somehow think is
unbiased, and that they

00:59:48.290 --> 00:59:49.890 align:middle line:90%
know unvarnished truth.

00:59:49.890 --> 00:59:50.690 align:middle line:90%
And I'm like, no.

00:59:50.690 --> 00:59:52.985 align:middle line:84%
You had a deeply psychologically
meaningful experience,

00:59:52.985 --> 00:59:54.560 align:middle line:84%
a psychologically
real experience.

00:59:54.560 --> 00:59:58.070 align:middle line:84%
But you don't get to tell me
what's true for me at all.

00:59:58.070 --> 01:00:01.220 align:middle line:84%
And that's the problem, I think,
when people get up on stages

01:00:01.220 --> 01:00:03.320 align:middle line:90%
and start playing Messiah.

01:00:03.320 --> 01:00:08.000 align:middle line:84%
Psychedelic guruism
makes me allergic,

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:09.270 align:middle line:90%
and I think it does you, too.

01:00:09.270 --> 01:00:10.070 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

01:00:10.070 --> 01:00:12.950 align:middle line:84%
I mean, rule one
for me is nobody

01:00:12.950 --> 01:00:14.468 align:middle line:90%
gets to make meaning for you.

01:00:14.468 --> 01:00:16.760 align:middle line:84%
The minute somebody else
starts making meaning for you,

01:00:16.760 --> 01:00:18.470 align:middle line:90%
you just run.

01:00:18.470 --> 01:00:20.670 align:middle line:90%
That's rule one.

01:00:20.670 --> 01:00:22.910 align:middle line:84%
So what I want to elaborate
on-- and the second thing

01:00:22.910 --> 01:00:24.410 align:middle line:84%
William James said
is he said, look,

01:00:24.410 --> 01:00:26.070 align:middle line:84%
I think all these
states are the same.

01:00:26.070 --> 01:00:29.180 align:middle line:84%
I think flow states,
and trance states,

01:00:29.180 --> 01:00:31.892 align:middle line:84%
and out-of-body experiences,
and psychedelic--

01:00:31.892 --> 01:00:33.100 align:middle line:90%
I think they're all the same.

01:00:33.100 --> 01:00:35.473 align:middle line:84%
What's amazing-- all
right, this is a guy who--

01:00:35.473 --> 01:00:37.640 align:middle line:84%
this was the guy who came
up with the idea of stream

01:00:37.640 --> 01:00:38.490 align:middle line:90%
of consciousness.

01:00:38.490 --> 01:00:40.510 align:middle line:84%
And he wanted to
measure how long.

01:00:40.510 --> 01:00:44.330 align:middle line:84%
He figured out that the now
is 12 seconds long by timing

01:00:44.330 --> 01:00:45.890 align:middle line:90%
his thoughts with a stopwatch.

01:00:45.890 --> 01:00:48.830 align:middle line:84%
This is experiments
in like 1900, right?

01:00:48.830 --> 01:00:50.740 align:middle line:90%
Here's the funny thing.

01:00:50.740 --> 01:00:52.490 align:middle line:84%
The now is actually
14 seconds long.

01:00:52.490 --> 01:00:53.290 align:middle line:90%
So he was off.

01:00:53.290 --> 01:00:56.060 align:middle line:84%
He was really close,
besides the point.

01:00:56.060 --> 01:00:59.950 align:middle line:84%
But what we now know 110 years
later is he was totally right.

01:00:59.950 --> 01:01:04.630 align:middle line:84%
So if you look under the hood of
flow, psychedelic experiences,

01:01:04.630 --> 01:01:07.060 align:middle line:84%
trance states, out-of-body
experiences, meditative states,

01:01:07.060 --> 01:01:10.630 align:middle line:84%
we roughly see the same three
or four things happening.

01:01:10.630 --> 01:01:11.620 align:middle line:90%
There are differences.

01:01:11.620 --> 01:01:15.065 align:middle line:84%
You get way more serotonin and
a lot of psychedelic experiences

01:01:15.065 --> 01:01:15.940 align:middle line:90%
and blah, blah, blah.

01:01:15.940 --> 01:01:17.080 align:middle line:84%
So there's differences,
but they're

01:01:17.080 --> 01:01:18.550 align:middle line:90%
roughly the same experience.

01:01:18.550 --> 01:01:21.580 align:middle line:84%
And what this means is-- for
example, let's take trauma.

01:01:21.580 --> 01:01:24.060 align:middle line:84%
Today, we have all
kinds of options.

01:01:24.060 --> 01:01:27.670 align:middle line:84%
So you referenced my friend,
Rick Doblin's early experiments

01:01:27.670 --> 01:01:28.750 align:middle line:90%
with Michael Mithoefer--

01:01:28.750 --> 01:01:31.870 align:middle line:84%
PTSD and MDMA--
where they found one

01:01:31.870 --> 01:01:33.700 align:middle line:84%
to three sessions
of MDMA therapy

01:01:33.700 --> 01:01:36.790 align:middle line:84%
was enough to either totally
take people off their meds

01:01:36.790 --> 01:01:38.590 align:middle line:84%
or completely reduce
their use, right?

01:01:38.590 --> 01:01:39.890 align:middle line:90%
That was amazing.

01:01:39.890 --> 01:01:42.340 align:middle line:84%
And that was done with
soldiers returning

01:01:42.340 --> 01:01:45.880 align:middle line:84%
from wars in Afghanistan, and
Iraq, and with victims of child

01:01:45.880 --> 01:01:48.050 align:middle line:90%
abuse and sexual abuse.

01:01:48.050 --> 01:01:51.520 align:middle line:84%
And then the Army came
along and said, OK, well, we

01:01:51.520 --> 01:01:53.380 align:middle line:84%
need that kind of
healing for our soldiers,

01:01:53.380 --> 01:01:55.690 align:middle line:84%
but we don't want to
use a psychedelic.

01:01:55.690 --> 01:01:59.500 align:middle line:84%
Let's try to substitute flow
and more specifically, the flow

01:01:59.500 --> 01:02:02.120 align:middle line:84%
produced by surfing
and talk therapy.

01:02:02.120 --> 01:02:03.970 align:middle line:84%
So the same thing in
psychedelic therapy

01:02:03.970 --> 01:02:06.100 align:middle line:84%
where you had psychedelic
and talk therapy.

01:02:06.100 --> 01:02:08.800 align:middle line:84%
They just used
surfing as a producer,

01:02:08.800 --> 01:02:10.810 align:middle line:84%
as a trigger for flow
and talk therapy.

01:02:10.810 --> 01:02:14.920 align:middle line:84%
And they found that five weeks
of surfing, plus talk therapy

01:02:14.920 --> 01:02:18.250 align:middle line:84%
was enough to completely
cure or significantly reduce

01:02:18.250 --> 01:02:19.630 align:middle line:90%
instances of PTSD.

01:02:19.630 --> 01:02:22.030 align:middle line:84%
And then they came back a
couple years later and said,

01:02:22.030 --> 01:02:25.480 align:middle line:84%
OK, let's try meditation
and talk therapy.

01:02:25.480 --> 01:02:27.760 align:middle line:84%
And they found that four
weeks of meditation and talk

01:02:27.760 --> 01:02:30.790 align:middle line:84%
therapy-- not quite as effective
as the other two technologies,

01:02:30.790 --> 01:02:32.960 align:middle line:84%
but again, significant
reduction in medication.

01:02:32.960 --> 01:02:39.450 align:middle line:84%
And the point is that whether
it's skills or healing,

01:02:39.450 --> 01:02:41.783 align:middle line:84%
a lot of what nature
designed us to do

01:02:41.783 --> 01:02:43.450 align:middle line:84%
was to shift our state
of consciousness.

01:02:43.450 --> 01:02:44.250 align:middle line:90%
That's how.

01:02:44.250 --> 01:02:46.235 align:middle line:84%
So creativity is
a great example.

01:02:46.235 --> 01:02:49.965 align:middle line:84%
We have overwhelming evidence
that we suck at training people

01:02:49.965 --> 01:02:51.090 align:middle line:90%
to be more creative, right?

01:02:51.090 --> 01:02:53.350 align:middle line:84%
It's the most important
skill in the 21st century.

01:02:53.350 --> 01:02:54.808 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't matter
if you're talking

01:02:54.808 --> 01:02:57.060 align:middle line:84%
about qualities in a CEO
or what our kids need

01:02:57.060 --> 01:02:57.960 align:middle line:90%
to learn in school.

01:02:57.960 --> 01:02:59.255 align:middle line:90%
Creativity tops every list.

01:02:59.255 --> 01:03:01.380 align:middle line:84%
And we suck at training
people to be more creative.

01:03:01.380 --> 01:03:04.927 align:middle line:84%
And the reason is we keep trying
to trade up a set of skills.

01:03:04.927 --> 01:03:07.260 align:middle line:84%
What we need to be doing is
training up a state of mind,

01:03:07.260 --> 01:03:08.550 align:middle line:84%
because that's how
we're creative.

01:03:08.550 --> 01:03:09.780 align:middle line:90%
We switch our consciousness.

01:03:09.780 --> 01:03:12.870 align:middle line:84%
That also turns out
how we heal trauma.

01:03:12.870 --> 01:03:15.300 align:middle line:84%
And metabolized trauma,
also in a big way,

01:03:15.300 --> 01:03:16.740 align:middle line:90%
is switch our consciousness.

01:03:16.740 --> 01:03:18.840 align:middle line:84%
The simple explanation
is I always tell

01:03:18.840 --> 01:03:20.400 align:middle line:84%
people, if you're
ever heartbroken,

01:03:20.400 --> 01:03:23.380 align:middle line:84%
you want to get over it
really fast, go skydiving.

01:03:23.380 --> 01:03:25.020 align:middle line:90%
Simplest, literally.

01:03:25.020 --> 01:03:29.730 align:middle line:84%
Because with trauma, it's just
pathways in the brain, right?

01:03:29.730 --> 01:03:31.920 align:middle line:84%
It's like water
carving a canyon.

01:03:31.920 --> 01:03:32.850 align:middle line:90%
Everything goes there.

01:03:32.850 --> 01:03:34.975 align:middle line:84%
And nothing is more powerful
than the [INAUDIBLE]..

01:03:34.975 --> 01:03:36.330 align:middle line:90%
So you need an experience.

01:03:36.330 --> 01:03:37.530 align:middle line:90%
>> Shake the snow globe.

01:03:37.530 --> 01:03:38.010 align:middle line:90%
>> You need to--

01:03:38.010 --> 01:03:38.280 align:middle line:90%
right.

01:03:38.280 --> 01:03:40.072 align:middle line:84%
As Robin Carhartt Harris
says at Imperial--

01:03:40.072 --> 01:03:42.330 align:middle line:84%
I friended-- you
shake the snow globe.

01:03:42.330 --> 01:03:44.320 align:middle line:84%
You need an experience
that is more powerful--

01:03:44.320 --> 01:03:45.120 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

01:03:45.120 --> 01:03:47.640 align:middle line:84%
>> --than the thing that crushed
you to create a new memory,

01:03:47.640 --> 01:03:48.020 align:middle line:90%
right?

01:03:48.020 --> 01:03:48.820 align:middle line:90%
>> 100%.

01:03:48.820 --> 01:03:50.910 align:middle line:84%
>> And so one of the things
psychedelics will do--

01:03:50.910 --> 01:03:53.850 align:middle line:84%
>> So they say you need one
nail to take out the other nail.

01:03:53.850 --> 01:03:55.020 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:55.020 --> 01:03:56.700 align:middle line:90%
But it's so interesting.

01:03:56.700 --> 01:03:59.440 align:middle line:84%
Because some people will
say to get over heartbreak,

01:03:59.440 --> 01:04:00.255 align:middle line:90%
meet a new girl.

01:04:00.255 --> 01:04:02.130 align:middle line:84%
But what you're saying
goes deeper than that.

01:04:02.130 --> 01:04:03.840 align:middle line:84%
Because you're saying
neurobiologically,

01:04:03.840 --> 01:04:05.715 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't have to just
be meet a new person.

01:04:05.715 --> 01:04:07.740 align:middle line:84%
Just go have a new
experience that

01:04:07.740 --> 01:04:10.990 align:middle line:84%
is so powerful that the
presence supersedes the past.

01:04:10.990 --> 01:04:12.390 align:middle line:84%
Because when you're
heart-broken,

01:04:12.390 --> 01:04:15.540 align:middle line:84%
the whole point is you're not
living in the present, right?

01:04:15.540 --> 01:04:17.850 align:middle line:84%
She broke up with you,
or he broke up with you.

01:04:17.850 --> 01:04:22.320 align:middle line:84%
And now, every present moment
is tainted by the past, right?

01:04:22.320 --> 01:04:25.920 align:middle line:84%
David Lenson calls it
temporal dislocation.

01:04:25.920 --> 01:04:28.230 align:middle line:84%
And he was talking about
what happens to people

01:04:28.230 --> 01:04:30.460 align:middle line:90%
with bad trips on drugs.

01:04:30.460 --> 01:04:33.305 align:middle line:84%
But I think it applies to sober
states when your heart-broken--

01:04:33.305 --> 01:04:34.680 align:middle line:84%
>> By the way, I
do want to say--

01:04:34.680 --> 01:04:35.930 align:middle line:90%
>> --which is also a bad trip.

01:04:35.930 --> 01:04:40.260 align:middle line:84%
But he basically says that
the past trauma is now

01:04:40.260 --> 01:04:42.540 align:middle line:90%
over-determining the present.

01:04:42.540 --> 01:04:44.070 align:middle line:84%
And by over-determining
the present,

01:04:44.070 --> 01:04:46.050 align:middle line:84%
it means that what's
happening now--

01:04:46.050 --> 01:04:47.040 align:middle line:90%
we're fine.

01:04:47.040 --> 01:04:48.420 align:middle line:90%
But I'm seeing dark.

01:04:48.420 --> 01:04:50.880 align:middle line:84%
I'm seeing black, because
of that past trauma.

01:04:50.880 --> 01:04:53.140 align:middle line:84%
And then by over-determining
what's happening now,

01:04:53.140 --> 01:04:55.140 align:middle line:84%
bringing that anxiety
into what's happening now,

01:04:55.140 --> 01:04:58.260 align:middle line:84%
I'm now conjuring up a future
that becomes identified

01:04:58.260 --> 01:05:00.720 align:middle line:90%
with doom, death, despair.

01:05:00.720 --> 01:05:03.420 align:middle line:84%
Hyperpression
[INAUDIBLE] of mortality

01:05:03.420 --> 01:05:06.700 align:middle line:84%
is an integral part of
every bad psychedelic trip.

01:05:06.700 --> 01:05:07.593 align:middle line:90%
The doom, doom.

01:05:07.593 --> 01:05:09.510 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to make
it past the next moment.

01:05:09.510 --> 01:05:12.300 align:middle line:84%
The essence of a
panic attack is that.

01:05:12.300 --> 01:05:15.210 align:middle line:84%
I'm dying right
now, so to speak.

01:05:15.210 --> 01:05:18.470 align:middle line:90%
And so he says that when--

01:05:18.470 --> 01:05:20.760 align:middle line:84%
but he says
eventually the present

01:05:20.760 --> 01:05:22.290 align:middle line:90%
will supersede the past.

01:05:22.290 --> 01:05:25.770 align:middle line:84%
So enough time passes
that you can overcome

01:05:25.770 --> 01:05:27.870 align:middle line:90%
this temporal dislocation.

01:05:27.870 --> 01:05:30.120 align:middle line:84%
Or you can have a sufficiently
powerful experience

01:05:30.120 --> 01:05:34.170 align:middle line:90%
that's positive that replaces--

01:05:34.170 --> 01:05:38.970 align:middle line:84%
it just dissipates that
wedge, that trauma.

01:05:38.970 --> 01:05:40.560 align:middle line:90%
That's David Lenson's idea.

01:05:40.560 --> 01:05:41.880 align:middle line:90%
What were going to say?

01:05:41.880 --> 01:05:44.060 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh.

01:05:44.060 --> 01:05:45.890 align:middle line:90%
Yep, it's gone.

01:05:45.890 --> 01:05:47.090 align:middle line:90%
Totally gone.

01:05:47.090 --> 01:05:49.550 align:middle line:90%
Got lost in the Jason.

